<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Value of havens for abandoned children questioned  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PITTSBURGH (AP) - In the chill of a new spring, one baby was
found dead in the trash, another in a river - and Gigi Kelly, a
mother and registered nurse, came up with a simple idea.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Kelly organized a program she called Baskets for
Babies, encouraging families around the state to set out baskets
lined with warm blankets on their front porches, ready to take in
unwanted infants who might otherwise die.
</P>
<P>
   But more than a year later, the baskets of 600 members have yet
to receive a single baby - and more sophisticated programs aimed at
preventing infant abandonment are getting similarly dismal results,
even while mothers continue to abandon their children.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, not a single baby has been turned in since a law was
passed last year that offered a form of clemency to mothers who
leave children with designated medical providers. In Houston alone,
seven babies have since been abandoned, none with medical
providers, and one died.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey, however, saw the first use of its abandonment law
last week when an infant boy unwanted by his mother was turned in
to the pediatric emergency room at a Newark hospital. The
two-day-old boy was brought to the hospital on Thursday evening by
a police officer and a volunteer from an anti-abortion
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not for or against (safe havens),'' Joyce Johnston, a
spokeswoman for the Child Welfare League of America, told the
Pittsburgh Post-Gazette. ''But we do have some concerns about the
effectiveness of some of these programs, which don't seem to get at
real issues, like prevention.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is movement in 28 states - including Pennsylvania
- for legislation that would grant amnesty to mothers who abandon
newborns in a safe place. Some cities have already started their
own programs, including Pittsburgh, where Mayor Tom Murphy is
expected to unveil his plan Wednesday that will be operated by four
area hospitals. A nonprofit organization is raising money for an ad
campaign to get word of the Pittsburgh program out to those who
might need it.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Department of Health and Human Services survey counted 65
''discarded infants'' in 1991; eight of them died. In 1998, the
most recent year statistics were available, there were 105; 33 of
them died. That doesn't include 31,000 abandoned at hospitals in
1998, and some social workers believe the true numbers are much
higher.
</P>
<P>
   ''For every baby that's found, think about those (who) were
successfully drowned or buried, lost forever; and there's this
mother you never hear about with that terrible secret she carries
around for the rest of her life,'' said Mary Winter, a director at
Mom's House, a Pittsburgh agency that provides support services for
unwed pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   Cmdr. Gwen Elliott, head of the Pittsburgh Police's Sex Assault
and Family Crisis Unit, questioned whether a mother distraught
enough to abandon a child would be sufficiently rational to find a
safe haven instead.
</P>
<P>
   ''We once found a newborn in a picnic basket under a porch in
East Liberty, where the mother had placed a bottle and a rattle,''
said Elliott. ''She wanted to do the right thing, but she wasn't
reality-based. The idea of (going) someplace (safe) to drop off her
baby ... I don't think that would have occurred to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott also said if mothers trusted hospitals, they probably
would have sought prenatal care in the first place. She suggested
the money would be better used to encourage counseling for women
with unwanted pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, 75 billboards sprouted up around the city to promote
the program, with little success.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hate to say it's a failure. We don't really know yet,'' said
Judith Hay, a spokeswoman for the program's administrator, Harris
County Child Protective Services.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't really know who these women are. There just isn't any
good data or research on this. What is her state of mind? What kind
of law would prevent her from becoming a criminal?''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Child Welfare League of America: http://www.cwla.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
