<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United they stood at Democratic convention  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) - United was the official airline of last
week's Democratic National Convention. It was also the theme of the
New Jersey delegation that traveled here.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli and Woodbridge Mayor Jim McGreevey
exchanged cordial words just weeks after Torricelli tried but
failed to dislodge McGreevey as the presumptive nominee for
governor in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Warring power brokers George Norcross of Camden County and state
Sen. Raymond Lesniak of Union County exchanged an unlikely hug at a
party held by McGreevey.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Bradley paid an emotional visit to his home-state
Democrats and thanked them for their support, even though he
received few endorsements from New Jersey leaders in his
unsuccessful primary challenge to Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the 124-member delegation lavished praise on
their presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Many delegates from ethnically diverse New Jersey were inspired
by Gore's selection of a Jewish running mate, Connecticut Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, and moved by the convention speeches of Lieberman
and his wife Hadassah.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never thought it would happen in my lifetime. And the
acceptance has been extraordinary,'' said June Fischer of Scotch
Plains, a Jewish delegate who attended her eighth convention. ''For
me to stand and carry a sign that said 'Hadassah' is overwhelming.
I got misty-eyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Simon, the 29-year-old president of New Jersey Young
Democrats, said her peers will be energized at the idea of helping
elect the first Jewish vice president.
</P>
<P>
   She said she noticed ''a lot more young people out here as
delegates than in years before.''
</P>
<P>
   For some New Jersey candidates, the convention offered a chance
at brief national exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry Hill Mayor Susan Bass Levin, challenging Rep. Jim Saxton
of Mount Holly, introduced herself to America as a ''mother of two
wonderful daughters .. proud that our party has done so much to
help parents like me who want to find a balance between work and
family.''
</P>
<P>
   First-term Rep. Rush Holt of Pennington, a top target of
Republicans this fall, told the convention that as a scientist, he
understands ''that education and research and development are the
keys to keeping and expanding America's prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate candidate Jon Corzine used his time at the podium to
reject ''irresponsible and unjust tax cuts that would squander''
the federal budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Robert Menendez of Union City, the highest-ranking New
Jersey representative in House leadership, nailed down a prime
speaking spot on Wednesday to help nominate Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unlike the Republican convention, we Democrats don't need to
masquerade as inclusionary. We live that creed in every way - and
Joe Lieberman is a shining example,'' Menendez said.
</P>
<P>
   There were, however, some moments of discontent.
</P>
<P>
   LaQuetta Nelson, a delegate and president of a New Jersey
gay-rights group, objected that the delegation's breakfast meetings
never mentioned the needs of gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Also during the convention, some members of the Congressional
Black Caucus expressed concerns about Lieberman's position on
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman addressed black leaders on Tuesday and seemed to
win them over.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was good that the meeting was held, venting was done,
clarification was given and we can look forward,'' said Rep. Donald
Payne of Newark, a black congressman who attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ''I think overwhelmingly, almost unanimously in my
opinion, the Congressional Black Caucus will be 100 percent
supportive of the Gore-Lieberman ticket.''.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, the final word on the convention came from former
Gov. and perennial comedian Brendan Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne, attending his fifth convention, addressed the delegates
on the morning of the final day and lamented that party gatherings
no longer use his favorite song.
</P>
<P>
   And with that, he led the delegates in a chorus of ''Happy Days
Are Here Again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
