<HEADLINE> Militants Kill Four in Kashmir  </HEADLINE>
By BINOO JOSHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAMMU, India (AP) -- Militants with assault rifles barged into
the homes of two Hindu families in India's troubled Kashmir state,
killing at least four villagers and critically wounding two, police
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The assailants sprayed bullets on the sleeping villagers
Saturday night in Udhampur district, said Rajesh Kumar, the
superintendent of police.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second attack on Hindu villagers within 48 hours. On
Friday, six Hindus were shot and killed in Kotdhara village after
gunmen knocked on a door and began firing when it opened. Two
neighbors who rushed outside were among those killed. Six people
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Indian authorities blame Muslim militants for the attacks, but
none of Kashmir's separatist militant groups have claimed
responsibility. Nearly a dozen such attacks have left more than 120
civilians dead -- most of them Hindus -- during the past month.
</P>
<P>
   The Himalayan province of Kashmir is divided between India and
Pakistan, both of which claim it in its entirety. Islamic rebels
seeking independence for Kashmir or its unification with Muslim
Pakistan have fought for 11 years, leaving 25,000 people dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Hezb-ul Mujahedeen, the main guerrilla group in Kashmir,
declared a cease-fire last month and said it was ready to talk
peace with the Indian government. But it ended the cease-fire two
weeks later when New Delhi refused to include Pakistan in the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   In New Delhi, defense ministry spokesman Pramod Sharan Bhatnagar
said the government had ordered emergency funds to build civilian
bunkers in areas battered by shelling near the cease-fire line with
Pakistan. India and Pakistani forces regularly fire artillery
shells across the mountainous Kashmir frontier.
</P>
<P>
   India accuses Pakistan of arming and funding the insurgents in
Kashmir. Pakistan says it provides only moral support to the
guerrillas, not material help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
