<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinic Offers Hope for Dentaphobics  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE BAILEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Absolutely nothing gets Johnna Estep's
heart racing, palms sweaty and stomach in knots faster than the
thought of going to the dentist.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a child, my mom used to have to drag me in, literally
kicking and screaming,'' said Estep, 36, of Versailles. ''I would
get so worked up before I would go that I honestly couldn't
function.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Estep has learned to manage her 'dentaphobia' with
the help of a University of Kentucky professor and dentist who
specializes in treating adults with just such a paralyzing fear.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't treat teeth; I treat people,'' says Dr. Ted Raybould,
a professor of general dentistry and preventative medicine as well
as director of adult special patient care at the University of
Kentucky Chandler Medical Center. ''In the process, they get their
teeth taken care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Americans share Estep's phobia, which once kept her
from getting even a routine checkup for nearly five years. During
the past 16 years, Raybould has treated thousands of patients who
would rather be anywhere than tilted back in cold leather chairs
with sharp instruments in their mouths.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a true phobia,'' said Raybould. ''Some people are scared
of heights, some people are frightened by snakes or spiders and
some people are terrified of dentists.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Smith, a professor of behavioral science at the school, has
treated and referred hundreds of patients to Raybould over the
years, creating a two-man dental fear clinic at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fear of the dentist is a very common thing,'' said Smith.
''I've done three statewide surveys over the years in Kentucky, and
an average of 19 percent claim they have significant dental fear.
Surveys like this are done all over the country as well and the
results are similar. Neither time nor geography seem to change the
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the fear normally stems from some type of traumatic
event in a patient's life that grows stronger and more intense as
that person grows older.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm always amazed at the pain people will endure over a period
of months or even years to avoid seeing a dentist,'' he said.
''Nearly all of the people that I see haven't been to the dentist
for years, even for a routine cleaning or check up. They had a
negative experience early in their lives and, once they were old
enough that mom couldn't make them go, simply quit going because
the dentist was associated with pain and anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what happened to Estep. Often sick as a child,
she developed an intense fear of needles. That and several bad
experiences at the dentist made her loathe even the thought of
getting in the chair.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was about 5, my dentist would slap me on the leg and
one time I even peed in his chair,'' she said. ''He got so angry
and that was it for me. I've never been able to forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   Before ever peeking into patients' mouths, Raybould meets with
them in a non-threatening environment to discuss their fears and
treatment options.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to establish a rapport with the patient and gain
their trust or you have no shot,'' he said. ''So I meet with them
the first time and let them know we're not going to do any
treatment that day. Instead, we talk and try to figure out a way to
handle their dentistry in the way they can best tolerate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pain management causes the most anxiety, Raybould said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can do drugs by mouth or nitrous oxide,'' he said. ''But to
really foster the most amount of confidence, I'll have to do an
IV-conscious sedation where I can control the level of sleepiness
better than I can with the nitrous or oral drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of my patients are so fearful that we have to take them
to the operating room and use anesthesia to knock them completely
out. I currently have about 200 patients and about 75 of them
choose to go the operating room route, even for routine checkups
and cleanings.''
</P>
<P>
   Estep has been treated by Raybould for the past 15 years. Each
treatment, including a dreaded root canal, was performed while she
was under intravenous sedation.
</P>
<P>
   ''As soon as he puts the needle into my hand, I start talking to
him and just go to sleep,'' she said. ''When I wake up, it's all
over.''
</P>
<P>
   It took only a handful of visits before Estep felt that trust
and confidence that Raybould says is so important.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was completely at ease with him in no time,'' she said. ''I
learned quickly that when I come here I'm going to be fine, and
that he's going to do everything he can to make the experience as
painless as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   One way Raybould gains that trust is to let his patients know
they are in complete control of the process.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tell them right off that no matter what -- no matter where I
am in the procedure -- if you can't handle it, get up and walk right
out. I'm not going to force anybody to do anything,'' he said.
''That gives people confidence that they can make things happen --
or not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Raybould knows firsthand what his patients are experiencing. He
had negative episodes with dentists as a boy and, upon choosing
dentistry as a profession, decided he would focus on helping people
overcome some of the same anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it kind of developed naturally because I'm a fear
patient myself,'' he said. ''I was hurt by a dentist as a child and
I really empathize with these people.
</P>
<P>
   ''It also puts me in a position where I can train more residents
to help patients manage their fears. There's not enough of me to go
around, so I need to have other people out there doing what I'm
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Estep, for one, is thrilled with that prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a young woman, I have to keep my appearance up -- that's
very important to me,'' she said. ''I have to keep my teeth. That's
not negotiable. And I'm so thankful that Dr. Raybould has been able
to help me manage a fear that has been with me as long as I can
remember.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't ever say that I look forward to going to the dentist.
But I know that when I come now, it's going to be a breeze.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-20-00 1202 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000820.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Birds: A key to tracking West Nile virus  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HILL
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELMAR, N.Y. (AP) - Dead birds are piling up at Ward Stone's
door by the van load - a blue jay in a picnic cooler, frozen crows
packed in dry ice, sparrows, hawks and warblers.
</P>
<P>
   The birds are potentially infected with West Nile virus and
Stone, the state's wildlife pathologist, will pluck some out for
examination. Organs of sick-looking birds will then receive a final
diagnosis at a nearby state health lab, where Dr. Laura Kramer and
her staff are already inundated with hundreds of birds and
thousands of mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   This is how the West Nile virus is watched in New York state.
The disease's alarming spread this summer has been tracked mostly
through dead birds and mosquitoes. It's a huge and exhausting job.
Kramer's researchers work weekends, and her lab is running out of
space for specimen jars. Stone starts at 3 a.m. and works 16-hour
days to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think I go five minutes in a day without thinking of
West Nile,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile has become a very public health threat for a second
straight summer, with three elderly Staten Island residents testing
positive for the disease this year. All are recovering.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who contract the disease experience flu-like
symptoms. But the virus is more dangerous in children under 5, the
elderly and people with compromised immune systems. Given that
threat, New York is among the many eastern states on the lookout
for the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Birds and mosquitoes can act like a canary in a coal mine
because certain types of mosquitoes can carry the virus and the
birds contract it. Finding an infected animal in an area tips local
health officials off to the virus' presence. Cities can then decide
whether to roll out insecticide-spraying trucks or to take other
precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're an early warning system,'' said Stone.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a lot of warnings this summer, especially with
birds. As of Friday, 240 birds were diagnosed positive statewide.
Most of these birds were crows and most were found in the New York
City metropolitan area. But infected birds are now turning up
around upstate New York, indicating the virus is present statewide.
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of state health officials, counties and private
citizens have been shipping dead birds for months to the state
Department of Environmental Conservation's wildlife pathology lab
just south of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Stone and his small staff perform triage on the hundreds of
bagged and boxed birds arriving daily. They must decide which birds
to perform a necropsy on - fresh corpses are better than old ones,
crows are better indicators than some other birds.
</P>
<P>
   Stone looks for West Nile symptoms like lesions on the birds'
hearts or enlarged livers and spleens. If he finds symptoms in a
bird, four specimen jars are shipped to the state Health
Department's nearby Griffin Lab - one jar each for a bird's brain,
heart, spleen and kidney.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer's staff performs molecular tests on the tissue for a
final diagnosis. From the tight confines of a converted horse
stable, Kramer's arbovirus lab receives about 200 birds a week. On
top of that, tests are done each week on some 600 pools of
mosquitoes shipped in on dry ice from around the state.
</P>
<P>
   It adds up to a lot of work. Kramer came out from California in
May to head the lab and has been hustling to keep up since.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really am amazed at the level to which the virus has
spread,'' Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   New York is one of 17 states, along with the District of
Columbia, that keep surveillance on West Nile in cooperation with
the Centers for Disease Control. The states stretch along the
Atlantic and Gulf coasts from Massachusetts to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts vary among the states.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think any other states are handling the quantity or
doing as intense an analysis as New York is,'' said Linda Glaser of
the federal government's Wildlife Health Center in Madison, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The work is not expected to let up anytime soon. Kramer said the
virus is increasing. Stone said a let-up might not be in sight
until a little after Labor Day. With luck, disease-carrying
mosquitoes will perish with the first frost.
</P>
<P>
   The would give Stone a chance to get back to pathology work that
was put on a back burner, things like checking contaminated turtles
and diseased ducks. Kramer wants to spend the winter researching
West Nile research, instead of reacting to it.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York State Health Department:
http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Centers for Disease Control and Prevention:
http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvbid/westnile/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
