<HEADLINE> Airman to be buried in Florida, 56 years after WWII bomber crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PITTSBURGH (AP) - Robert Kearsey left Florida for the slag piles
and steel mills of the Pittsburgh suburb of McKees Rocks, where
many managed to find work despite the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 56 years after he was killed in a World War II bomber crash
in China, Kearsey is going home.
</P>
<P>
   Kearsey and nine others who perished in the crash will be
honored in a burial service at Arlington National Cemetery in
Arlington, Va., on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the airmen will be buried at Arlington after Monday's
ceremony; but Kearsey's remains, and those of three others who died
in the crash, will be or have already been released to their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Kearsey will be buried later in Jacksonville, Fla., where his
family now lives and where a plot has been set aside to memorialize
him and his brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Two farmers found the crash site while searching for rare herbs
on 7,000-foot Kitten Mountain in Guangxi Province in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials have spent the intervening years gathering
and identifying the remains of Kearsey and the others, which were
most recently examined at the Defense Department's forensic
laboratory in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Another Pennsylvanian who died in the crash, Staff Sgt. Anthony
DeLucia, was buried earlier this month in his hometown of Bradford,
McKean County.
</P>
<P>
   Kearsey was 27 and single when he died. His nieces and nephews
plan to attend the Arlington service to honor his memory.
</P>
<P>
   They consider him a hero because he requested a dangerous
overseas combat post instead of accepting stateside duty to which
he was originally assigned.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kearsey's younger brother, Grady, followed him to western
Pennsylvania's steel mills, but both were in the service by 1943.
</P>
<P>
   Grady Kearsey was killed that summer when his Army Air Corps
plane was shot down over Germany, though his body was never found.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kearsey was transferred to a base in Langley Va. after
his brother's death, but felt guilty about finishing the war as a
stateside gunnery instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ''His motivation was to get even,'' said Grady Robert Kearsey,
56, a nephew named after both uncles.
</P>
<P>
   The Army fulfilled Robert Kearsey's request to return to active
duty.
</P>
<P>
   A bombing attack on Takao Harbor in Taiwan was his last mission.
The B-24 helped pound Japanese boats and docks, then headed home
but instead crashed into the side of Kitten Mountain on Aug. 31,
1944.
</P>
<P>
   The other airmen on the bomber were identified as 1st Lt. George
H. Pierpont of Salem, Va.; 2nd Lt. Franklin A. Tomenendale of
Shabbona, Ill.; 2nd Lt. Robert L. Deming of Seattle, Wash.; 2nd Lt.
George A. Ward of Jersey City, N.J.; Sgt. Ellsworth V. Kelley of
Newark, Ohio; Pfc. Charles Buckley of Garden City, Kansas; Staff
Sgt. William A. Drager of Washington, N.J.; and Private Vincent J.
Netherwood of Kingston, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
