<HEADLINE> H.Kong Immigration Officer Mourned  </HEADLINE>
By MARGARET WONG
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Top Chinese officials were among about a
thousand mourners at the funeral of a civil servant who died after
an arson attack at Hong Kong's immigration headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration senior officer Leung Kam-kwong, 42, died two weeks
ago from burns suffered when a group of illegal mainland migrants
set off an explosion at the government office. It was Hong Kong's
most violent episode in a simmering debate over residency rights.
</P>
<P>
   Leung and residency rights seeker Lam Siu-sing, 26, who died on
the same day, were among 50 people injured in the Aug. 2 attack.
Four of the seven people still hospitalized Sunday were in serious
condition, a government spokeswoman said. A total of 21 mainlanders
face charges related to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration from mainland China is the most delicate issue to
confront the island of Hong Kong since it reverted from British to
Chinese sovereignty three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong says it must control immigration to avoid having its
social services overwhelmed by millions of new citizens. But
thousands of mainlanders are in Hong Kong illegally and fighting to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong government has battled in court to limit the
number of migrants, at one point last year persuading Beijing to
overrule Hong Kong's top court in a case that had favored migrants
who sought a better life in capitalist Hong Kong. The border with
the mainland is still tightly controlled.
</P>
<P>
   At the funeral parlor Sunday, mourners sobbed quietly as two
immigration officers with black bands strapped on their left arms
placed a national flag on Leung's coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Mainlanders seeking the right of abode in Hong Kong expressed
sorrow for Leung and frustration over their own future.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was completely innocent. He was there to carry out his duty
only,'' said Wu Hong-kun, a 34-year-old illegal migrant from Fujian
Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
