<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koreas Plan More Reunions in Sept.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- North and South Korea are likely to
hold a second round of reunions for separated relatives in
mid-September, South Korea's Red Cross chief said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on a KBS-TV program, Chang Chung-shik, president of
South Korea's National Red Cross, said he discussed the issue
during a visit to North Korea last week.
</P>
<P>
   Chang led 100 South Koreans who visited the reclusive, communist
North for four days of temporary reunions with long-lost kin. An
equal number of people from North Korea visited Seoul for reunions
which ended Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I discussed with North Korean Red Cross officials the
possibility of arranging another reunion for dispersed family
members around Chusok,'' Chang said. Chusok, or thanksgiving day,
falls on Sept. 12 and is a major holiday in both Koreas.
</P>
<P>
   In an Aug. 12 meeting with 46 South Korean media executives,
North Korean leader Kim Jong Il promised to arrange more reunions
in September and October.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.2 million North Koreans fled to South Korea before or
during the 1950-53 Korean War, and thousand of South Koreans are
believed to have gone to the North voluntarily or after being
drafted into the North's army. The two Koreas are separated by a
heavily militarized border, and people on one side have been unable
to contact those on the other for almost half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Following last week's successful reunions, Seoul is under public
pressure to expand the program. South Korean officials said
reunions will be a major topic at a second round of high-level
inter-Korea government talks to be held in the North's capital,
Pyongyang, next week.
</P>
<P>
   The first round of talks was held in Seoul late last month, when
the Koreas agreed to reconnect a railway across their border. They
also reopened border liaison offices.
</P>
<P>
   The talks, led by Cabinet-level officials, are a follow-up to an
accord reached at a historic summit of the two sides' leaders in
June. The summit between Kim Jong Il and South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung provided the best chance yet for peace on the divided
Korean peninsula.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
