<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Ends World Youth Day in Rome  </HEADLINE>
By ELLEN KNICKMEYER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Pope John Paul II closed his latest World Youth Day
on Sunday with an invitation to the next one, in Toronto in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before we leave this great and beautiful gathering, I want to
announce that the next World Youth Day will be held in Toronto''
two summers from now, John Paul told a crowd of an estimated 2
million young pilgrims at Tor Vergata outside Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now I invite the young people of the world to set out
for Toronto,'' the pontiff said.
</P>
<P>
   A delegation of Canadian officials had an audience with the pope
later in the day. Afterward, they praised the Rome event.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll go back energized with lots of experience,'' said the
Rev. Thomas Rosica, who will be the director of Toronto's World
Youth Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian delegation said it would cost about $120 million to
host World Youth Day and that Toronto had ample meeting space for
large crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can handle very easily a million and half to 2 million
young people,'' said Mike Harris, the Ontario premier. ''Probably
there will be some temporary requirements, as in Tor Vergata, but
we don't need new massive structures.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegation, which also included Mayor Mel Lastman, said
Toronto was first advanced as a candidate a few years ago at the
World Youth Day in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hosting Youth Days 2002 in Toronto is a great opportunity and
a real gift to the Canadian church and the town,'' said the
president of the Canadian Conference of Catholic Bishops, the Rev.
Gerald Weisner.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul started World Youth Days in 1985 in Rome, drawing
200,000 people. The largest crowd it has drawn was 4 million
pilgrims, in the Philippines in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
