<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Part-time residents seeking votes at the shore  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - A voting-rights struggle has emerged
at the New Jersey shore - with a twist.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the debate are using slogans that date back to the
Revolutionary War. But while most such debates have involved
marginalized members of society, it is the largely affluent owners
of second homes at the shore who are demanding a say in the towns
where they pay property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a classic example of taxation without
representation,'' Philadelphia resident Marvin Levin, who also owns
a home in Ventnor, told The Press of Atlantic City for Sunday's
editions.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials and many year-round residents of shore towns
oppose changing voting rights in New Jersey, saying that would
violate the principle of ''one person, one vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They have a vote in the community where they reside,'' said
Brigantine Mayor Phil Guenther.
</P>
<P>
   Guenther also said certain year-round services, such as
education, could be shortchanged if people who do not send their
children to local schools nonetheless vote on budgets.
</P>
<P>
   ''People who live here year-round have more of a stake and
should have more of a say than those that live here for two or
three months at a time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite elements of class conflict, the argument comes down to
whether voting rights are based on residency or property ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Several states, including Connecticut and Tennessee, allow local
governments to decide whether to grant voting rights to nonresident
property owners. Residents of resort towns in New York, Michigan
and Massachusetts have asked for similar laws in their states.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Assemblyman Gerald Zecker, who represents parts of
Essex and Passaic counties, has introduced a resolution proposing
an amendment to New Jersey's constitution to permit nonresident
property owners to vote in local elections.
</P>
<P>
   Brigantine resident Tina Chaplin, who supports the resolution,
said summer residents' inability to vote increases the contrast
between them and full-time residents. Chaplin used to spend only
her summers in the resort town and the rest of the year in
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ''A person who lives on a park bench can have a vote, but a
businessperson who works hard and lives in the community cannot?''
she asked. ''That just doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill went nowhere in the state Senate, where it was opposed
by Republican Sen. Bill Gormley, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley, who represents Atlantic County, said allowing
nonresidents to vote runs counter to the America's basic democratic
principles.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what this country was based on,'' he said. ''It's just
such a fundamental part of what our society is about, I'd never
vote to change that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
