<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stolen Hall of Fame memorabilia resurfacing in catalogues  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) - Federal investigators are tracing the
trails of six baseballs signed by U.S. presidents, photos, and
other items worth millions that were stolen from the Baseball Hall
of Fame more than 25 years ago before resurfacing in catalogs, a
newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Four baseballs signed by presidents have been recovered, but the
FBI is looking into who took them during a time when security there
was more relaxed than officials say it is today, according to The
Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly the collection of Walter ''Big Train'' Johnson, who was
inducted in 1939, the balls were stolen in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall quietly filed a police report.
</P>
<P>
   ''We felt it was better at the time to say nothing to publicize
this,'' said Howard Talbot, Hall of Fame director from 1976 and
1993. ''We hoped they would resurface and we'd get them back.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, Hank Thomas, Johnson's grandson, went to
Cooperstown expecting to find his grandfather's treasures. When the
collection was missing, Thomas was shocked.
</P>
<P>
   He said his family should have been contacted about the missing
collection and wanted to know why there seemed to be no effort to
recover the stolen balls.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was the most frustrating thing of all,'' Thomas said.
''They just gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the only theft in Cooperstown's history.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-1980s, when the value of baseball memorabilia
inflated, the Hall of Fame may have been an easy target.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the heist of the balls, worth millions today, a
Joe DiMaggio cap was stolen from a display locker. Hall of Fame
officials put another one there, wiring it to lockers. But wire
cutters were used to remove the second cap.
</P>
<P>
   When officials put plexiglass over the display lockers, people
pulled pieces of jersey through air vents and cut away scraps.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, photos and World Series programs were commonly
found at memorabilia shows sporting the Hall of Fame stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas himself saw a baseball signed by President Warren Harding
in a catalog. When Thomas demanded an investigation, it was
returned to the Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The surfacing of items attracted attention from federal
investigators, who are now working with Hall of Fame officials and
professional baseball, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know if the balls we sold were the ones that were
stolen,'' said Bill Mastro, founder of Mastronet Inc., which had
been advertising presidential baseballs. ''None of our balls had
the Hall of Fame markings.''
</P>
<P>
   Mastro said last year, the FBI asked for a list of presidential
ball-buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ''But none of my buyers have told me the FBI took their item,''
he said. ''We would have given them their money back.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame said no one was available to comment on the
story Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-20-00 1351 </TRAILER>
