<HEADLINE> Former Spy To Return to Britain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALAIS, France (AP) -- Former British spy David Shayler said
Sunday that he has decided to risk arrest and return home to
Britain after nearly three years in France as a means of proving he
did ''nothing wrong'' in leaking information about British
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference in the French port town of Calais, Shayler
repeated his allegations that British foreign intelligence officers
were involved in a plot to assassinate Libyan leader Moammar
Gadhafi -- a claim the government denies.
</P>
<P>
   Shayler, who worked for Britain's domestic espionage agency MI5
from 1994 until 1997, expected to sail to Dover with his family and
girlfriend Monday after three years in France, where he fled after
selling stories to a British newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that I've come back should send a very strong signal
to people that I have nothing to fear,'' Shayler said. ''I have
done nothing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old former agent spent four months in Paris' La
Sante prison in 1998 before French authorities refused to extradite
him to Britain for trial under the Official Secrets Act.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate civil suit filed last December by the British
government, Shayler is accused of breach of copyright and breach of
contract for releasing secret documents.
</P>
<P>
   Shayler said he believed he would be charged and then freed on
bail upon his return to Britain. Despite the risk of arrest on
arrival, he said he is determined to go home to clear his name.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did what I did because I love my country,'' he said. ''I'm
not a traitor to it. ... What I did was free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Shayler's lawyer, John Wadham, said his client had always hoped
for ''a proper investigation'' of his allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's why he produced the information in the first place,''
Wadham said.
</P>
<P>
   Shayler claimed the Metropolitan Police Service was
investigating his allegations on the Gadhafi plot.
</P>
<P>
   He expects to face a trial in Britain, and said he hoped to use
European human rights laws to challenge any charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   The former spy said he spent three difficult years in France
trying to raise money to return home.
</P>
<P>
   During his time here, he wrote a novel, ''The Organisation,'' a
fiction story he has described as ''a gritty thriller about spies,
sex and football.'' This summer, British government censors
screened the book without making changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
