<HEADLINE> Ricky loves 'I Love Lucy'; Hillary prefers Curly and Moe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Sure, Hillary Clinton and Rick Lazio disagree on
important issues. But how do they differ on the little things, like
what to do for fun or what to eat for breakfast?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, he likes ''I Love Lucy'' (a guy named Ricky would)
while she can do the finger-snapping fist-banging routine from
''The Three Stooges.'' He never drinks coffee, but she'll take it
any way you make it. Here, then, are some of the personal opinions
Lazio and Clinton hold about matters less weighty than Middle East
peace - but in some ways, just as telling.
</P>
<P>
   FAVORITE SNACK FOOD, JUNK FOOD OR COMFORT FOOD:
</P>
<P>
   RL: Entenmann's Crumb Cake.
</P>
<P>
   HRC: Fruit and chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   BREAKFAST:
</P>
<P>
   RL: I don't eat breakfast often, but when I do scrambled eggs
and a little toast.
</P>
<P>
   HRC: Depends on how I'm feeling when I wake up. Could range from
eggs and bacon to oatmeal to nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   HOW DO YOU TAKE YOUR COFFEE?
</P>
<P>
   RL: I don't drink coffee.
</P>
<P>
   HRC: Lotsa cream - but sometimes black! Sometimes it's
cappuccino and sometimes it's espresso ... You're not going to get
easy answers from me.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   BEST THING ABOUT LIVING IN A HIGH-TECH WORLD:
</P>
<P>
   RL: The advances that we've made in biology, biological
discovery, which have been possible because of advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
   HRC: One of the best things about information technology is the
way it's helped us to map the human genome. ... I couldn't live
without e-mail, fax and copy machines.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   WORST THING ABOUT HIGH-TECH WORLD:
</P>
<P>
   RL: Annoying cell phone rings.
</P>
<P>
   HRC: There is no end to the day. You can be beeped. You can be
faxed, you can be e-mailed, you can be called, you can be
interrupted no matter where.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   FAVORITE TV SHOW FROM CHILDHOOD:
</P>
<P>
   RL: ''I Love Lucy.''
</P>
<P>
   HRC: ''The Three Stooges.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
