<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newark Airport monorail to close for repairs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Just over four years after it opened, the
monorail at Newark International Airport is closing for massive
repairs that are expected to last into the winter months.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Labor Day, the 30,000 people who take the six- to
eight-minute monorail daily will return to buses for the time being
- rides that could take 30 to 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing cracks and corrosion on the tracks caused by cold weather
will cost the contractors who built the monorail $25 million, but
some who were involved in the original construction say the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey is partly to blame.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sunday's editions of The Record of Hackensack, the
Port Authority, the bistate agency that runs the airport and
oversaw the contract, failed to foresee major problems, despite the
failure of a test ride six weeks before the monorail opened.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bulk of the responsibility has to lie with the Port
Authority,'' said Roy Pleasant, a former Port Authority official
who was brought in to oversee the project years after construction
had begun.
</P>
<P>
   ''The design was inherently weak, but its demise was hastened by
the materials used, and the method of construction was flawed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency admitted that it made a mistake in choosing a
monorail design that had never been used at an airport or in cold
weather, and needed upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   But Frank Lombardi, the Port Authority's chief engineer,
defended the choice of monorail, conceding only that the design
should have undergone more testing.
</P>
<P>
   ''You needed a system that would make that shuttle run as easily
as possible,'' he said. ''Given the constraints we have with the
way the terminals are laid out, this is the best system we can
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Lombardi said the contractors ''are totally responsible'' for
the damages requiring the massive repairs.
</P>
<P>
   The system cost $354 million to purchase, design and build and
took five years to finish. It was supposed to last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Before the rail was built, passengers at the Newark airport rode
buses to move among terminals, parking lots and rental car
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''A number of carriers wanted to bring foreign flights to Newark
but couldn't because passenger movement time, from customs to
domestic gates, was so unpredictable,'' Pleasant said. ''They could
not guarantee making connections because buses took 45 minutes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
