<HEADLINE> Moderate Quake Rocks Taiwan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Two moderate earthquakes rocked central
Taiwan on Sunday, seismologists said. No injuries or damages were
immediately reported.
</P>
<P>
   The first, a magnitude 4 temblor, struck at 9:46 a.m. Its
epicenter was 1.3 miles southwest of Chiayi city, which is about
110 miles south of the capital, Taipei, the Central Weather Bureau
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was followed by a 4.4-magnitude quake at 2:59 p.m. Its
epicenter was 8.5 miles southeast of Taoyuan city, which is about
125 miles south of Taipei, seismologists said.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan is often hit by tremors because it sits atop two tectonic
plates, which are huge, moving slabs of the Earth's crust.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of minor tremors and aftershocks have rattled Taiwan
since a 7.6-magnitude quake devastated parts of central Taiwan in
September, killing about 2,400 people and destroying thousands of
homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
