<HEADLINE> Moderate Quake Rocks Eastern Turkey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- A moderate earthquake rattled eastern
Turkey early Sunday, sending panicked residents jumping from
balconies and out windows. At least nine people were reported
injured.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude-4 quake hit the city of Erzurum just after
midnight Sunday, the Anatolia news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   No serious damage was reported in Erzurum, 560 miles east of
Ankara. But a soldier was critically wounded when he threw himself
out of the second floor of a military barracks in a panic, reports
said. One woman suffered a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   The epicenter of the quake was about 20 miles southwest of the
city, just along the Palandoken fault. Two aftershocks followed,
Erzurum's Ataturk University observatory said.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey's entire eastern region sits on an earthquake-prone belt.
A magnitude-6.8 earthquake ravaged Erzurum and its environs in
1983, killing more than 1,300 people.
</P>
<P>
   Two strong quakes killed some 18,000 people in Turkey's
northwest last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
