<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAA data shows despite Burlington crash, airways are not more crowded </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The collision of two small planes above a
tract of suburban homes in Burlington Township two weeks ago has
caused concern that New Jersey skies are becoming dangerously
crowded.
</P>
<P>
   However, federal registrations of small aircraft in New Jersey
and neighboring states show the number of these planes has not
increased in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, aircraft counts provided to The Associated Press by the
Federal Aviation Administration's registration office in Oklahoma
City show that since 1995, the number of small planes of various
types based in the state has declined slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Oklahoma City register and assign numbers to all
noncommercial aircraft classified under the heading ''general
aviation'' - privately owned planes and corporate aircraft,
including small jets.
</P>
<P>
   Their data shows that in July, 4,636 planes were registered to
New Jersey owners, corporate and private. That is a drop of 2.3
percent from 1995, when 4,745 planes were registered. In the same
period of time, New Jersey added 300,000 cars and trucks to its
roads, for a current total of about 5.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a perception that when you say that the two airplanes
came together in the sky, that automatically means that the skies
are too crowded,'' said Emmitt O'Hare, director of the
Transportation Department's office that monitors aviation.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a tractor trailer driving down the road hits a house, then
people say there are too many tractor trailers on that road,''
O'Hare said. He said the Burlington collision that killed 11
''could have just as easily happened over the Pinelands, or over
Arizona. It was a great tragedy, and it was very, very unfortunate,
but it does not mean there is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   While the FAA has exclusive jurisdiction over general aviation
since the planes cross between states so easily, O'Hare's state
agency reviews applications for airfield expansion. The state has
49 airports, and all but a handful are rural fields used
exclusively for general aviation.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's aircraft trend holds true for its neighbors, where
aircraft can readily cross into the state.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, aircraft registration has decreased 3.6
percent in Pennsylvania and 2.5 percent in New York. It held steady
in Maryland. New Jersey and its three largest neighbors combined
had 26,218 aircraft registered in July, down 2.3 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is Delaware, where aircraft registrations leaped
60 percent, from 6,100 in 1995 to 9,700 last month. Officials
attribute this to the state's popularity as a corporate
headquarters location because of its low business taxes, making it
likely the majority of those aircraft never cross or touch down in
that state.
</P>
<P>
   The trend in New Jersey and its neighbors is not typical.
Nationally, general aviation is up, with 178,310 planes registered
in July, an increase of about 10 percent from 1995. But by 1999
that rate of growth had slowed to less than one percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Those who monitor general aviation look at other statistics to
draw a picture of what is going on. For instance, while the number
of aircraft increased only 10 percent nationally since 1995, flight
time increased 14 percent and fuel consumption increased 54
percent. Such figures were not readily available by state.
</P>
<P>
   These flight and fuel trends show more of the larger,
twin-engine aircraft are in use for business purposes, planes that
despite the Aug. 9 tragedy in Burlington County are considered the
safest of general aviation in part because they usually have
professional pilots.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare said his office is not responsible for investigating the
Aug. 9 crash, and neither for that matter is the FAA, although the
agency is tasked with monitoring overall aviation safety. The
National Transportation Safety Board is investigating the
collision.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the Burlington crash, U.S. Sen. Frank Lautenberg,
D-N.J., an influential lawmaker in aviation issues, has called upon
the FAA to examine whether unregulated travel should be permitted
to continue for small aircraft over New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Told of the FAA figures showing no increase in the number of
aircraft, the senator's office issued a statement Friday saying he
still wanted the question studied.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether it's more people flying due to our strong economy, or
more flights per day coming in and out of New Jersey, I want to
make sure that the FAA's safety measures can keep pace with the
amount of air traffic,'' Lautenberg's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, O'Hare said state officials do not take lightly
requests to expand airfields, which they do regulate. Organized
protests have met the proposal to expand the South Jersey Regional
Airport in Lumberton, just a few miles from the Aug. 9 crash,
though neither plane involved came from there.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare said the environmental impact airfield owners are
required to assess includes the noise increase air traffic will
produce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-20-00 1532 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
