<DOCNO> APW20000820.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middlesex court workers break occupancy law  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) - Nine judges and their staffs
unwittingly broke the law when - for the past two weeks - they
illegally occupied the Middlesex County Family Court building.
</P>
<P>
   City inspectors denied the new building a certificate of
occupancy for various safety reasons. But the judges and 150
courthouse workers were told they could move into the building Aug.
7.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of a county employees union said they learned of the
lack of certificate after workers complained that the air
conditioning in the building had failed and an interpreter became
trapped in one of the courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ''How can you administer justice when you're in a building
that's breaking the law,'' Jeff Demos, a shop steward for
Communications Workers of America Local 1034, told The Star-Ledger
of Newark for Sunday's editions. ''It impacts upon the integrity of
the (judicial) system.''
</P>
<P>
   The construction company, Keating Building Corp., has taken
responsibility for the mistake, saying it happened because company
officials believed they would have the certificate in time.
</P>
<P>
   Project manager Bruce Auerbach said the safety of courthouse
employees was never an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the safety systems were in place, fully operating the
fully tested by the city, prior to the move,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach said the company received a temporary certificate on
Friday, after showing that the air conditioning was working
properly.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said Keating was being fined the maximum of $500
a week until the building's problems are corrected.
</P>
</TEXT>
