<HEADLINE> Allman Plays Benefit for Loved Ones  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDIAN, Miss. (AP) -- Gregg Allman says the benefit concert he
played Saturday night was the least he could do for fiancee Stacey
Fountain and her father, who was seriously injured in a motorcycle
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Allman, a founding member of the Allman Brothers Band, says they
helped him overcome his addictions to drugs, alcohol and
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stacey is one special person,'' Allman said, after the
concert. ''She stood by me through sobering up. We stopped smoking
together. I've been married a few times before, but those
relationships were nothing like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Allman, 52, said he battles addiction demons every day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Been sober four years. First year was hard, but not now,'' he
said. ''Cigarettes, you have to go moment to moment with those. But
what you have to remember is the urge will leave you just as quick
as it comes.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 4,200 fans donated a minimum of $10 each at the
concert. The money was to be used to pay the hospital bills of
Allman's fiancee's father.
