<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Sides To Tense Hebron Story  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEBRON, West Bank (AP) -- Husam Jabari, a vegetable vendor in
Hebron, says the trouble started when Jewish settlers marched in
and overturned market stalls.
</P>
<P>
   David Wilder, a Jewish settler, says it began when fruits and
vegetables flew out of the market, aimed at Jewish worshippers
returning home for a quiet Sabbath meal.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever version of Saturday's clash you hear, both sides draw
the same conclusion: A recent escalation in violence in this
troubled West Bank town is attributable to last month's Camp David
summit -- and Hebron, a sensitive flashpoint, has the potential to
pose a real obstacle to Israeli-Palestinian peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient town, home to 130,000 Palestinians, is known for its
religious fervor. Hamas, the militant Islamic group that rejects
Israel's existence, does well in elections here.
</P>
<P>
   But Hebron is also home to 400 Jews who see themselves as
guardians of Judaism's second-holiest city, the site of the tomb of
biblical patriarchs worshipped by Jews, Christians and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   The Jews here are among the hardest-line of the Jewish settlers
living in the heavily Palestinian West Bank. Parties that advocate
emptying Israel and the West Bank of Arabs do well here and in the
neighboring settlement of Kiryat Arba.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't want us to be here,'' David Wilder said of the
Arabs. Minutes earlier, Husam Jabari said of the Jews: ''They don't
want us here.''
</P>
<P>
   Such feelings are not new. Relations reached their nadir in
1993-94, the year when a series of Jews were killed and Baruch
Goldstein, a Jewish Kiryat Arba doctor, gunned down 29 Muslim
worshippers in a mosque. That act nearly scuttled nascent peace
talks, and a repeat could undermine efforts to convene another
Mideast summit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a truce of sorts has been maintained since 1997, when
Israel handed much of Hebron to Palestinian control. Israel still
administers the quarter in the center of the city where the Jews
and about 30,000 Arabs live.
</P>
<P>
   Things began to deteriorate on July 15, when Shlomit Arnon -- the
14-year-old daughter of Noam Arnon, the Jewish community's leader --
claimed she was sexually assaulted by an Arab during a stroll. She
told police her screams drove off her attacker.
</P>
<P>
   That led settlers to attack Arab passers-by and rampage through
the market, a warren of covered stalls that spills into the
glistening paved stones of the Jewish enclave. Israeli troops
separated the sides.
</P>
<P>
   That incident occurred during Camp David, when news first leaked
that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak was ready to make
far-reaching concessions to the Palestinians. Palestinians said
settler fears of further concessions led to the riots -- a bid, they
say, to scuttle the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''When something happens in the United States, they take it out
on us here,'' Jabari said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder, who helps administer the Hebron Jewish community, also
blamed Camp David -- for encouraging the Arabs around him to believe
they can attack with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been told by the Arabs that they expect our expulsion as
a result of Camp David,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern has repeated itself at least three times since then.
On Saturday, the spark was a traffic incident. A Palestinian cabbie
hit a 13-year-old Jewish boy, injuring his leg; the cabbie fled the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Jabari said Palestinian vendors in the market started packing up
their stalls as soon as they heard of the hit-and-run, knowing that
stall-overturning was inevitable. He wasn't quick enough with his:
He said he lost about $625 in the subsequent attack, biting into
his monthly profits of $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of Arabs starting the provocations made no sense,
Jabari said -- they had everything to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not like a government is running things here, it's like
the mob,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder did not deny the overturned stalls, but he said it was
the culmination of a day of frustrations, including stoning
incidents. The last straw was when the Arabs taunted settlers by
tossing tomatoes and fruit at them, Wilder said.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing Jabari's why-disrupt -life argument, he said the
settlers couldn't be at fault.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one would start this just as the Sabbath lunch is
beginning,'' Wilder said of his religious community. ''On the
Sabbath, I want to eat and sleep and pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilder said it was hard for settlers to accept that what would
be considered a simple hit-and-run -- or sexual assault -- elsewhere
is not part of an organized effort to intimidate Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a limit to how long people can sit and say 'Maybe he
didn't mean it,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side appears ready to trust the other anytime soon. On
Sunday, the Hebron Jews held a memorial service for 67 Jews
massacred by Arabs in 1929 riots -- an act that led survivors to
flee the town, ending hundreds of years of a continuous Jewish
presence. Jewish settlers returned after the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
   ''They lived a pious life, in friendship with their Arab
neighbors,'' Noam Arnon eulogized at the cemetery, which overlooks
Hebron's cluttered tumble of ancient and modern dwellings. ''Then
they were slaughtered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
