<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nursing shortage causes some families to step in for patient care  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey nursing organizations and unions
say years of staffing cutbacks are catching up with hospitals in
the form of a nursing shortage. The shortage is apparent to some
patients' relatives, who say they have had to step in to help busy
nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ''When my son was in the hospital, I always stayed with him, and
pretty much everyone I know does, too,'' Sharon Kroll, of
Annandale, told The Star-Ledger of Newark for Sunday's editions.
The Hunterdon County woman's 6-year-old son, who has a seizure
disorder, has been hospitalized five times, mostly at Robert Wood
Johnson University Hospital in New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not due to lack of caring,'' Kroll said. ''It's just that
the nurses are so busy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past 20 months, the state Department of Health and Senior
Services has cited 9 hospitals so far this year for failing to keep
enough nurses on their floors, said Marilyn Dahl, who oversees
enforcement for the department. That's more than the number of
facilities cited in all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   The fine amounts have increased, prompting the New Jersey
Hospital Association to argue recently that a nursing shortage is
making it difficult for hospitals to fill jobs, especially in areas
where specialized nursing skills are required.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would rather use that money to recruit nurses than to pay
fines,'' said Geri Moon, vice president of hospital operations for
the association.
</P>
<P>
   But union representatives say hospitals created the problem in
the mid-1990s, when many nursing schools were closed and hospitals
cut tuition programs that helped nursing aides become more skilled.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hospitals can't now say, 'Where did all the nurses go?' They
cut nurses,'' said Jeanne Otersen, a spokeswoman for the Health
Professional and Allied Employees, a nurses union. ''Nurses are
leaving the business.''
</P>
<P>
   A May survey by the New Jersey Hospital Association reported the
average nurse-to-patient ratio at most hospitals for general care
floors is 1-to-6 during day and 1-to-7 or 8 patients at night.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Nurses Association has said many of its members
report taking care of 10 or 12 patients.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes I look down the hall and see three, even four call
lights on,'' said Jean Cunningham, a nurse for 23 years at Pascack
Valley Hospital in Westwood, Bergen County. ''You think, where do
you go first?''
</P>
<P>
   Nurses said in many cases, families are staying with
hospitalized relatives. Some change bandages, feed and dress
patients to help them to the restroom. Others have hired private
nursing aides to sit bedside with elderly patients.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most people won't leave their parents in the hospitals by
themselves; they stay overnight,'' said Helen Litvak, who chairs a
support group in Livingston for women with aging parents. ''In our
group, people feel the nurses may not be able to answer the call
bell.''
</P>
<P>
   But nurses say families can't do the job of nurses. Nurses are
better able to assess how a patient is doing, said Stephanie
Orrico, a nurse at Englewood Hospital and Medical Center since
1974.
</P>
<P>
   Several hospitals have tried to attract nurses by making hours
flexible for working mothers. Others are considering hiring nurses
from overseas or are offering sign-on bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Despite financial difficulties hospitals face, they must
continue to improve working conditions to keep qualified nurses and
attract new ones, said Irma Lupia, a lobbyist for the New Jersey
Nurses Association.
</P>
<P>
   Lupia said nurses have left hospitals to work at insurance
companies, schools and doctors' offices. Some have left nursing
entirely to sell real estate or start businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to work hard to get those nurses back in hospitals,''
Lupia said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-20-00 1618 </TRAILER>
