<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore leads Bush by 10 points in NJ  </HEADLINE>
The Associated Press:
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Democratic National Convention boosted Vice President Al
Gore to a lead of 10 percentage points over Republican George W.
Bush in New Jersey, according to the latest Gannett New Jersey
poll.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the poll, released Sunday, show Gore leading the
Texas governor 44 percent to 34 percent. A similar poll taken just
after the Republican National Convention two weeks ago showed Bush
leading Gore by 9 points.
</P>
<P>
   Before the conventions, the candidates were running about even
in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Among those whose votes are undecided is Alice Bass of
Lavallette, who said she is a registered Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm waiting for a debate,'' she said. ''I want to see how they
handle themselves when they both have to answer the same
question.''
</P>
<P>
   Results released Sunday of a national poll by CNN-USA
Today-Gallup had Democrat Gore at 47 percent, Republican Bush at 46
percent, Green Party candidate Ralph Nader at 3 percent and Reform
Party candidate Pat Buchanan at 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those interviewed in the New Jersey poll said Gore deserved
credit for choosing as his running mate Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the
first Jewish candidate for that office. But 51 percent thought the
choice wouldn't affect the campaign either positively or
negatively. Twenty-five percent thought the choice of Lieberman
would help Gore, and 17 percent thought it would hurt his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey poll indicated that New Jersey Senate candidate
Jon Corzine did not fare as well as the vice president. Corzine's
lead over Republican Bob Franks was 2 points, one point down from
the 3-point lead he held after the Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 429 people who were registered and identified as
likely voters were interviewed for the poll. The margin of error is
plus or minus 4.8 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-three percent of New Jersey voters say Gore should not
be linked with the sex scandals of the Clinton administration,
according to the poll.
</P>
<P>
   But 56 percent also said he played just a little part in the
administration's achievements, compared with 30 percent who said he
played a big part in those achievements and 5 percent who said he
played no part in them at all.
</P>
<P>
   ''The American people are funny,'' said Robin Collier of
Sayreville. ''Many people will try to link him to the sex scandal,
and they shouldn't. He had no part in it. But Republicans are
trying awfully hard to make the link. And they don't want to give
him credit for the economic policies, but he deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the news that another grand jury had been impaneled
to investigate the president in connection with the Monica Lewinsky
matter, 68 percent said they thought the matter should be over, and
24 percent agreed with the decision to continue the inquiry. The
rest were undecided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
