<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Gov. Race May Affect Peace  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE DEL RIO, Mexico (AP) -- There are no polling places for
Sunday's election in this tiny village on the muddy road to La
Realidad.
</P>
<P>
   The nearest voting is a couple of hours away by foot. Most say
they won't bother.
</P>
<P>
   But even if many don't vote from this village near La Realidad --
the unofficial capital of the Zapatista rebels -- backers of the
rebels will have much to do with whether the new governor elected
in the Chiapas state elections succeeds. These are the first
elections held since the party that ruled Mexico for 71 years was
toppled in the July 2 presidential vote.
</P>
<P>
   The still-unresolved Zapatista revolt looms over Chiapas
politics. The past six years have seen four governors, three of
them emergency replacements for men driven from office by crises
linked to the Zapatista revolt.
</P>
<P>
   Both Sami David of the governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party and Pablo Salazar of an eight-party coalition claim they
would be most effective at helping end a struggle that got the
world's attention on Jan. 1, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   On that date, the Zapatista National Revolutionary Army staged a
rebellion to demand greater justice and democracy for Chiapas' poor
Indians. Though open warfare lasted only two weeks, the guerrilla
presence in the state's jungle canyons has led to repeated clashes
between emboldened dissident groups and pro-government forces.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's voting, electoral officials and observers had
reported only scattered problems by midday. Businessmen in jackets
lined up to vote alongside barefoot Indian women toting infants in
brightly embroidered shawls as the polls opened near the cathedral
in San Cristobal de las Casas.
</P>
<P>
   For some, voting was an act of courage.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors of a 1997 massacre of 45 people in the village of
Acteal marched for four hours through the mountains to vote in Los
Chorros, the town that had expelled them and home to many of their
paramilitary attackers.
</P>
<P>
   State officials failed to install polling places for absentee
voters near the towns where the refugees are sheltered.
</P>
<P>
   ''The greatest fear the people have in coming to the polls is
suffering an attack by the paramilitaries along the way,'' said
Agustin Vasquez Ruiz, spokesman for the Las Abejas group of
refugees from the Los Chorros area.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,000 polling places were scattered throughout Mexico's
poorest and most rural state, one where disputes over land,
religion and Indian rights have often erupted into violence. It is
a tough place to govern.
</P>
<P>
   In 176 years, the state has had more than 160 governors --
despite Mexico's practice of six-year terms over the past six
decades.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose del Rio is only 105 miles from the state capital,
Tuxtla Gutierrez, but a hard six-hour's drive, some on tracks
unpassable to most cars. The unofficial Zapatista capital of La
Realidad is an hour by dirt road to the east.
</P>
<P>
   The impoverished coffee farmers in this Lacandon Jungle canyon
describe themselves as rebel ''sympathizers,'' but they show the
discipline of Zapatista stalwarts. While friendly, few will talk
politics. None will give his name, saying they are forbidden to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   All say they are ''neutral'' in the election, echoing Zapatista
communiques. And they express a studied lack of enthusiasm for
either candidate.
</P>
<P>
   An Indian man with bare feet and ragged pants who denounces
capitalist exploitation says there will be no interference with the
election, ''so they cannot say it is the fault of the EZLN,'' the
rebel movement's Spanish initials.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about President-elect Vicente Fox's promise to meet key
Zapatista demands and renew peace talks, the man replies: ''We
still do not know if he will comply.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When they are in their positions of power, they forget about
the Indians,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks after Fox ended 71 years of rule by the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, Salazar holds a strong lead in most polls over
David, despite the fact Chiapas has been a PRI stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI has sent some of its top national campaigners to aid
David -- who has a reputation as a PRI reformist -- hoping to halt a
national crisis of party confidence caused by its first
presidential loss.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar is a former PRI senator who quit the party last year,
arguing that it should move faster to solve the Zapatista revolt
and accusing the state government of backing paramilitary groups to
battle the Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   As senator, he was a member of a commission that negotiated a
partial peace deal with the Zapatistas rejected by the federal
government. He says his election would be a key element in bringing
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not friends'' with the Zapatistas, he said in a recent
interview. ''I know them from the negotiations. I am not a
Zapatista. But they have a great advantage with me: I am not
anti-Zapatista.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants to give the Zapatistas ''the dignified out they
have been fighting for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-20-00 1747 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
