<DOCNO> APW20000820.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> May, Woods Share Lead at PGA  </HEADLINE>
By RUSTY MILLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Bob May, hardly a household name, was
holding his own with the biggest name in golf.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Californian, who started the day a shot behind
Tiger Woods at the PGA Championship, led by as many as two shots
early Sunday but was tied with Woods midway through the final round
at Valhalla Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Woods began his round at 13 under, with May and Scott Dunlap at
12 under. Woods lost a three-shot lead midway through the third
round when he double-bogeyed the 12th and had a bogey at the 15th.
A two-putt birdie on the closing hole gave him sole possession of
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, seeking his third major title of the year, continued to
have difficulty in the final round.
</P>
<P>
   After a huge drive on the 1st hole, he hit his second shot to 8
feet but missed the downhill birdie putt. At the par-5 2nd hole, he
hit another big drive but his 4-iron second shot sailed into the
rough right of the green. His downhill chip rolled past the pin and
into the fringe. From there, he chipped 4 feet past the hole -- and
missed the putt for bogey.
</P>
<P>
   His playing partner took advantage.
</P>
<P>
   May, who has never won a PGA Tour event, saw his second shot at
the 2nd hole land in the gaping bunker on the left side of the
green, but he blasted out to 3 feet and hit the birdie putt. The
two-shot swing put him a stroke ahead of Woods.
</P>
<P>
   May found the deep rough off the tee on the par-4 4th. But his
iron shot landed softly on the green and gently rolled over a ridge
to within 2&AMP;frac12; feet of the cup. The birdie that followed gave him a
two-shot advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Both May and Woods bogeyed the 6th. May hit over the green and
failed to get up and down, while Woods three-putted from 45 feet
after finding the deep rough off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   Woods started his comeback after hitting into the no-man's-land
between the two fairways at the par-5 7th. He recovered with a shot
into the right fairway, then chipped to 6 inches for a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   At the 166-yard 8th hole, Woods knocked his iron shot to 10 feet
and made the birdie putt to pull even with May at 13 under.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Langham, a Georgian making his first appearance in any
major championship, was alone in third place at 12 under.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Maria Olazabal, who set the course record and tied the
Grand Slam tournament low with a 63 in the third round, was at 11
under, along with Denmark's Thomas Bjorn, Stuart Appleby, Greg
Chalmers and Dunlap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-20-00 1812 </TRAILER>
