<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kerik tours precincts, tastes ethnic NYC on first day  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Newly minted Police Commissioner Bernard Kerik
spent his first day in office on Sunday meeting cops in precinct
houses and visiting a Baptist church in Brooklyn, where he asked
the black congregation to ''give me a chance'' in the demanding
job.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Joseph Dunne, who was named
first deputy commissioner after losing out to Kerik for the top
post, Kerik promised to ''reach out to the community'' and try to
forge a new degree of mutual respect between the 41,000-member
department and the city's minorities.
</P>
<P>
   A decorated former narcotics detective and longtime friend of
Giuliani who has won praise for jail reforms as the city's
commissioner of corrections, Kerick was named by the mayor on
Saturday to succeed Howard Safir, who resigned to take a post in
private business.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from the pulpit at the small Greater Bright Light
Missionary Baptist Church in East New York, Kerik described himself
as a ''hands on'' executive and asked the several dozen worshippers
to tell other people that ''I'm going to work with the community.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I want you to tell them one thing - 'give him a chance,''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik, seeking to reassure listeners that he would not tolerate
police misconduct while reducing crime, cited a sweeping reduction
in jailhouse violence during his tenure as corrrections chief as
evidence of his ability and strategic approach.
</P>
<P>
   He said stabbings and slashings had been reduced from 120-130 to
only four or five a month, and incidents leading to someone being
hospitalized with injuries were down by 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did it by talking and interacting and using equipment we
never had before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerick also showed little patience with police department
critics who had attacked his appointment almost as soon as Giuliani
announced it. ''They don't even know me. They have nothing to do
with me. They have never interacted with me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, said earlier that Kerik should focus first on
issues of police brutality, and Rev. Al Sharpton faulted Giuliani
for failing to consult with community leaders before picking a
chief cop.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also scoffed at the critics of Kerik's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't win with some people,'' he said. ''We're doing
everything we can to reach out. There are people who make their
reputations, and their money, criticizing the police department.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerik, Dunne and Giuliani sat in a front row with City Council
member Priscilla Wooten, a deaconess in the church, and gathered
with other worshippers at the altar as the pastor, Rev. H. DeVore
Chapman, segued from his fire-and-brimstone sermon into a
hand-clapping hymn.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling that John the Baptist sought to preach in ''lifting
language'' to his audiences, Chapman said, ''We've got to change
the rhetoric - we need some lifting language,'' he said. ''We're
looking for somebody we can talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   The new commissioner began the day by attending roll call at the
33rd precinct in Washington Heights, near his Riverdale home, then
visited other precincts in Brooklyn on the way to East New York.
Later, he, Giuliani and Dunne marched in Brooklyn's Puerto Rican
parade in Williamsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Another organization frequently critical of Giuliani's policies
announced a 30-day ''moratorium'' to allow Kerik time to become
familiar with his new post and the department's issues.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Eric Adams, founder and president of One Hundred Blacks
in Law Enforcement, said he would ask Kerik to meet and ''start a
dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a good faith measure,'' Adams said in a telephone
interview. ''We want to express our desire to work with the new
police commissioner on improving relations in communities of color
and share some of our initiatives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-20-00 1846 </TRAILER>
