<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins' Arrington a Non-Starter  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH WHITE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- Even though LaVar Arrington is finally
showing some big-play ability for the Washington Redskins, coach
Norv Turner makes it sound increasingly likely the No. 2 overall
draft pick will not be in the starting lineup on opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington forced a fumble, recovered a fumble and had three
tackles, including a jarring hit on running back Rahshon Spikes for
a 3-yard loss, in Saturday night's 24-0 exhibition victory at
Cleveland. Arrington also got to the play with the first-string
unit for the first time, replacing Greg Jones in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington also showed some flashes of someone who could dominate
a game, a vast improvement from the tentative, out-of-shape
linebacker who debuted against Tampa Bay two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more to playing strongside linebacker than dashing
full-throttle toward the backfield every play. Turner said Sunday
that the game plan against Cleveland played to Arrington's
instinctive strengths, and it wasn't the well-rounded performance
needed to move ahead of fourth-year veteran Jones on the depth
chart.
</P>
<P>
   ''He did exactly what I know he can do -- he can make big
plays,'' Turner said. ''We did some things specifically for him. We
blitzed him. The thing we have to do is get LaVar to where he
doesn't give up big plays or negative plays. I think he's
progressing in that area, and that just comes from learning the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're in great shape there with Greg Jones as the
starter and LaVar as the backup. In a regular season game, I could
see both of them playing. We found a nice mix for the two guys
because Greg certainly gives us stability and experience in the
spot. LaVar gives us some of that big play ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrington's training camp was hampered by a weeklong holdout,
after which he showed up nowhere near football shape. By contrast,
the Redskins' No. 3 overall draft pick, tackle Chris Samuels, was
instantly made a starter after a brief holdout and has been
impressive since his first practice.
</P>
<P>
   On draft day in April, it seemed improbable -- barring injury --
that Arrington would not be starting and making an impact on
opening day. The fact that the Redskins can show some patience
further demonstrates how deep the team is.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game showed several more examples. Skip Hicks scored
two touchdowns, yet he's fighting for the second-string running
back job with Adrian Murrell. Backup quarterback Jeff George was
9-of-14, including a rifle shot to Albert Connell for a 36-yard
touchdown. Kenard Lang, a defensive end playing tackle while Dan
Wilkinson recovers from a knee injury, batted down three passes.
</P>
<P>
   The one area of concern is still at center, where untested Mark
Fischer make his first start since Cory Raymer injured a knee.
Turner said Fischer did OK, but there were obvious plays that will
get a good analysis in the film room -- including one in which
Fischer tripped guard Tre Johnson, which allowed a blindside hit on
quarterback Brad Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ''He did fine,'' Turner said of Fischer. ''He needs to play a
little bit lower, but I thought he did a lot of good things.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said Fischer will start the opener against Carolina on
Sept. 3. Another backup center, Jay Leeuwenburg, will start at
guard that game because Johnson will be serving a one-game
suspension for striking an official last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-20-00 1850 </TRAILER>
