<HEADLINE> Titans' McNair: Shoulder Healed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Tennessee Titans quarterback Steve
McNair threw in practice Sunday for the first time in nearly a week
and he pronounced his sore right shoulder healed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The soreness is all gone,'' McNair said with a smile. ''I'm
looking forward to getting back out there. Today was just a little
taste.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair had been bothered by soreness in his throwing shoulder
for the past couple of weeks, and he sat out two practices before
playing the first half of the Titans' 30-3 exhibition victory over
the St. Louis Rams on Aug. 14. He had not thrown in practice since
that game and watched the Titans' 34-32 loss to the Philadelphia
Eagles on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, McNair threw in every drill except the last where the
Titans worked on correcting mistakes with Kevin Daft and rookie
Billy Volek. Coach Jeff Fisher was happy with what he saw from
McNair.
</P>
<P>
   ''He felt pretty good and was throwing well, had good velocity
on the ball,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   McNair will be busy this week as the Titans prepare for their
season opener at Buffalo the next two days before turning their
attention to the Chicago Bears for their final exhibition game.
Fisher said he may play McNair and several other starters through
halftime after resting them against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds very good to McNair.
</P>
<P>
   ''That'll be good for us to get into a rhythm and be ready for
Buffalo,'' McNair said. ''You've got to keep them in your mind. Now
we've got one preseason game to go, and we've got to get better in
order to be ready for Buffalo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
