<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Kills 2 Guard Agents in Spain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUESCA, Spain (AP) -- A bomb ripped apart a Spanish Civil Guard
car killing the two officers inside on Sunday in an attack blamed
on Basque separatists, the latest in a wave of deadly attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb, which was stuck to the vehicle with a magnet, went off
just after 6 a.m. in the eastern town of Sallent de Gallego near
Spain's border with France.
</P>
<P>
   A woman agent died instantly, while the second agent, a man,
died later in the hospital, police said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the blast,
but police blamed the separatist group ETA -- whose name is a
Basque-language acronym for Basque Homeland and Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The blast brought to 11 the number of deaths blamed on ETA since
it ended a 14-month truce last December. Violence has escalated
recently, with four people killed and 11 injured in attacks over
the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Fernandez Pereda, 32, was the first Civil Guard woman
killed in separatist violence. The 22-year-old man, Jose Angel de
Jesus Encinas, had only three months on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ''The car was absolutely pulverized,'' said Jose Luis Sanchez,
the mayor of Sallent de Gallego.
</P>
<P>
   Television images showed the car doors and parts of the chassis
scattered over several yards along with bloody rags and rescue
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez said residents near the bomb heard a vehicle driving
fast in the area an hour before the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ETA has killed some 800 people -- 204 of them Civil Guard members
-- in its 32-year-old war for independence on Spain's northern
Basque region on the border with France.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago Lopez Valdivielso, director general of the Civil Guard,
pledged an intensified crackdown. ''We're here today to cry and
honor our dead,'' he told reporters. ''It's a day of pain but you
can be convinced that, starting tomorrow, these deaths will be a
stimulus in the fight against ETA.''
</P>
<P>
   Spain's King Juan Carlos sent a telegram of condolences to
Valdivielso and condemned the ''brutal and cowardly murders.''
</P>
<P>
   Sallent de Gallego is in Spain's Huesca province, outside the
Basque region. Police have said ETA frequently uses Huesca to
transport explosives and members from France to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   After the attack, police found a car with false license plates
nearby. Bomb experts blew up the car, fearing it might contain
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish Interior Minister Jaime Mayor Oreja told reporters the
attackers likely fled over the Pyrenees mountains to the French
border nine miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens groups throughout Spain called for nationwide protests
for Monday morning while hundreds of mourners gathered in Sallent
de Gallego late Sunday at a ceremony for the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Huesca, police blew up a car loaded 220 pounds of
explosives found abandoned alongside a highway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
