<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Spends $9.6 Million in July  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID HO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush spent about $2 million a week
in the final month before receiving the Republican presidential
nomination even as his fund-raising total broke the $100 million
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent $9.6 million in July, bringing his total spending to
$97.2 million, according to records filed Sunday with the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who unlike Bush agreed to limit his
spending to $40.5 million in exchange for taxpayer subsidies, set
his own record in July by becoming the first presidential candidate
to receive $15 million in federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   During the primaries, the federal government matches the first
$250 of each individual contribution for presidential candidates
who limit their spending. Candidates were limited this year to a
maximum of $16.9 million in such funds.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did a very good job getting people excited about supporting
the campaign and raising small donations from individuals,'' Gore
campaign spokesman Douglas Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   An additional $673,000 in matching funds last month brought
Gore's total to $15.3 million, pulling him further away from the
old mark of $13.5 million set by 1996 Republican presidential
nominee Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also raised $85,000 for his campaign, bringing his total to
about $37 million, excluding the federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   During the same time, Bush raised about $4.3 million in
contributions, which combined with money raised for a legal and
accounting fund pushed his total to $100.1 million. Bush's record
fund raising was possible because he declined federal matching
funds for the primaries, allowing him to spend as much as he could
raise.
</P>
<P>
   The past record for fund raising in a single presidential race
belonged to Ross Perot, who for the general election in 1992 took
in $72.8 million, nearly all of it from his own pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Bush reached his figure on the strength of 350,000 different
donors to his presidential campaign in all 50 states -- three
quarters of whom gave $100 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Bush can no longer raise money because early this month he
accepted $67.6 million in taxpayer financing for the fall election.
Gore applied for the funds Friday after the end of the Democratic
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Through Election Day, both candidates are limited to spending
that federal aid and cannot raise private funds except to cover
legal and accounting costs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had about $6.4 million left in the bank at the end of July,
which carried him through to the convention and allowed him to get
a head start on the election by hiring more staff and opening
campaign offices.
</P>
<P>
   He spent nearly $2 million in July, bringing his total spending
including legal and accounting costs to $44 million for his
campaign. Gore's expenses included $5,000 to reimburse the
government for trips on Air Force Two.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had $4.2 million on hand at the end of July. Overall, he
has spent $25.3 million on media, $17.5 million on fund raising and
$13.6 million on travel, the Bush campaign reported.
</P>
<P>
   Gore initially spent a lot of money to fight off a challenge
from former Sen. Bill Bradley. But he defeated Bradley in the early
primaries, moved his headquarters from Washington to Nashville,
reduced his staff to cut costs and found himself with plenty of
money remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Federal Election Commission: http://www.fec.gov
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign: http://www.georgewbush.com
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign: http://www.algore2000.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
