<HEADLINE> Nazi Groups March in Hamburg  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMBURG, Germany (AP) -- Hundreds of neo-Nazis and anti-Nazi
activists held simultaneous demonstrations in this northern port
city Sunday under the watchful eyes of 2,200 police.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 neo-Nazis descended on a square in central Hamburg,
while 500 anti-Nazi activists held their own demonstration 1,000
feet away. No serious incidents were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The far rightists were granted permission to hold the
demonstration on Saturday, when the Constitutional Court in
Karlsruhe lifted an earlier state court ban on the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   After the ruling, leftists and other anti-Nazi activists said
they would stage their own counter demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Sunday, police in Erfurt in eastern Thuringia state said
they had detained 40 Nazi sympathizers for taking part in banned
gatherings Saturday to mark the 13th anniversary of the death of
Hitler's former deputy Rudolf Hess and for displaying Nazi symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Hess committed suicide in Berlin's former Spandau prison in
August 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In Dortmund, an officer investigating a complaint that a group
of men were shouting Nazi slogans on Sunday had to fire a warning
shot and call for help when one of the group threatened to beat him
with a club, police said. Seven men aged between 19 and 27 were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   In the northern town of Neumuenster, 20 miles south of Kiel,
police raided a neo-Nazi hangout called Club 88 after they were
tipped off to illegal plans to celebrate the anniversary of Hess'
death.
</P>
<P>
   Several CDs with pro-Nazi songs were confiscated, but no one was
arrested, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians have asked Neumuenster's Mayor Hartmut Unterlehberg
to cancel the Club 88's concession. The repeated 88 stands for the
eighth letter in the alphabet and is a neo-Nazi synonym for ''Heil
Hitler.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
