<HEADLINE> N.C. Power Cos. Battle Outages  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- More than 7,000 North Carolina homes and
businesses were still without power Sunday as crews worked to
restore service knocked out Friday by severe storms.
</P>
<P>
   Two deaths were blamed on the storms that pounded the state with
heavy rain, wind, lightning and hail.
</P>
<P>
   Duke Energy reported 7,400 outages remaining late Sunday
afternoon, mostly in the Charlotte area, down from a peak of more
than 100,000 outages Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Power &AMP; Light spokesman David McNeill said his
company's outages were repaired. At the peak, CP&AMP;L had 52,000
outages Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A 78-year-old man died Saturday in a Charlotte house fire caused
by heat from a candle that had been lit because there was no
electricity. North of Charlotte, a man drowned on Lake Norman while
trying to swim to a boat that was blown away by a storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
