<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millen: No Tackles While Officiating  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD FENDRICH
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was like old times for Matt Millen -- focusing intently on the
line of scrimmage, dodging blockers, hopping around right in the
thick of things on an NFL field. He was even wearing a uniform with
''55'' on it.
</P>
<P>
   The uniform, actually No. 155, had black and white vertical
stripes, though, and his soft cap had a camera the size of a
lipstick container on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Millen, a former linebacker and now a Fox Sports commentator,
worked as the umpire for a little more than a quarter Sunday during
the Tampa Bay Buccaneers' 31-21 preseason victory over the New
England Patriots in Foxboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The game was televised by Fox, and the stunt was the latest in a
series of attempts by the NFL and its broadcasters to try to boost
interest and ratings. The ''UmpCam'' Millen wore is one example.
Others include ABC putting comedian Dennis Miller in the ''Monday
Night Football'' booth, CBS moving its pregame show to a
glass-walled studio in midtown Manhattan, and the league adding
more doubleheader Sundays to the TV schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The good news in Foxboro, for all concerned, was that Millen
resisted any back-of-the-brain temptation to tackle anyone or bark
out defensive signals. Millen, who can be quite critical of
officials when he is in the broadcast booth, threw his flag only
once -- a halfhearted toss on a motion penalty that other officials
also flagged.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now I have a better appreciation for how tough the job is, how
fast it goes, the amount of concentration needed to know what your
reads are,'' said Millen, who won four Super Bowls with the
Raiders, Redskins and 49ers before retiring in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a better understanding of why a penalty is called. A
couple of times I pulled my flag halfway out and shoved it back in.
I would see a hold, but then you have to know where the ball is. If
it's away from the play, you have to let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   The rule of thumb for judging all officials' performances is:
They've done their job if you don't know they're there.
</P>
<P>
   By that standard, Millen failed miserably, through no fault of
his own. Fox announcers John Madden and Pat Summerall spent more
time analyzing Millen's performance than anything else going on in
the game while he was on the field for the third quarter and the
first five minutes of the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Madden frequently used the telestrator to draw yellow circles
around Millen -- just in case viewers couldn't find the oversized
umpire.
</P>
<P>
   ''He looks like he's going to hit something,'' Madden said.
</P>
<P>
   Joked Summerall: ''You think there's any danger Matt will like
this so much that he won't come back?''
</P>
<P>
   Millen did look comfortable setting up in the umpire's spot,
with the linebackers about 5 yards off the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   He occasionally pushed a defender out of his way, but seemed to
be where he should be on each play. On a fumbled punt return with
7:12 left in the third quarter, Millen aggressively went through
the pile of players to try to determine who recovered the loose
ball.
</P>
<P>
   The microphone he was wearing picked up Millen saying, ''Right
there, easy boys. Right there, we got it, we got it. Piece of
cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen, still in uniform, went into the broadcast booth when he
left the game, and graded his performance an A-plus.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he gave himself a mixed review.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mechanics of officiating weren't all there,'' he said. ''A
couple of times, I just got messed up in terms of which side the
ball comes in from. In terms of the physical part of it, that was a
piece of cake.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt like it was 10 years ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-20-00 2111 </TRAILER>
