<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rocky Trip To Little League Tourney  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) -- Plane problems almost did what no team
in Latin America could do -- keep the Little League team from
Maracaibo, Venezuela, out of Williamsport.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that the flight broke down made the kids a little
nervous but the coaches got them under control,'' interpreter Micah
Hughes said Sunday, speaking for manager Eduvino Quevedo.
</P>
<P>
   The team's flight left Thursday morning from Caracas on its way
to San Juan, Puerto Rico, but was forced to turn back after 15
minutes because of mechanical problems. After a delay of several
hours the team was able to fly to San Juan, where they stayed
overnight. The team then flew to Philadelphia on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that the flight encountered bad weather and
turbulence on both the San Juan and Philadelphia legs.
</P>
<P>
   ''That didn't have anything to do with (Sunday's) game,''
Quevedo after his team's 10-0 loss to Japan in the series opener.
''The kids regained their calm pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   COSTNER HONORED: Actor Kevin Costner will be one of three
people inducted into the Peter J. McGovern Little League Baseball
Museum Hall of Excellence on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The actor isn't being honored for his films, however. As a
pitcher for the Saticoy (Ventura, Calif.) Little League Braves,
Costner was a top pitcher. He threw several no-hitters and struck
out as many as 16 batters in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Costner in the Hall of Excellence will be Billy Hunter,
executive director of the NBA Players Association, and Dr. Robert
Stratta, a professor of surgery at the University of
Tennessee-Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   STADIUM ON SCHEDULE: The construction of a 5,000-seat stadium
next to Howard J. Lamade Stadium is right on schedule, Little
League spokesman Lance Van Auken said.
</P>
<P>
   The new stadium became a necessity with the World Series
expanding to 16 teams next year. The $6 million stadium will have
the same dimensions as the 10,000-seat Lamade Stadium and is
expected to open next June, Van Auken said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   BASELINES: Players of the Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, squad, which
will begin play Monday against Latin American, have dyed their hair
blonde. ... The Williamsport Chamber of Commerce estimates the
Little League World Series generates about $13 million each year
for the local economy. ... Associated Press photographer Paul
Vathis, who has covered the Little League World Series since 1954,
will throw out the first pitch before Monday's game between Dhahran
and Latin America.
</P>
</TEXT>
