<HEADLINE> PRI: Tolerated Violent Bosses  </HEADLINE>
By JULIE WATSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's ruling party admits it has tolerated
violent political bosses among its ranks -- but swears not to do so
anymore after a post-election battle that left at least 10 dead,
local media said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Armed supporters of a longtime political boss aligned with the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, opened fire on thousands
of loyalists of Chimalhuacan's new mayor Friday in the gritty city
of 490,000 on the outskirts of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ''The PRI takes its historic responsibility for having tolerated
leaders and groups in the party whose condemnable conduct causes
harm and destroys,'' the PRI's national leader Dulce Maria Sauri
told the Mexico City newspaper Reforma. ''But today we say enough
is enough! Never again!''
</P>
<P>
   Sauri said the party's top brass plans to expel such radical
political bosses from its ranks. The party is in the midst of
redefining itself after losing the presidency July 2 for the first
time in 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Mexico's ruling party negotiated with its potential
threats, offering them permits to run taxi businesses, bus routes
and subdivide land invaded by squatters.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the radical leaders of street vendors, trash pickers,
and poor neighborhoods promised their support and allowed the party
to rule Mexico for more than half a century with relative
stability.
</P>
<P>
   But in Chimalhuacan, Guadalupe Buendia went too far. Police now
are looking for Buendia for allegedly urging her supporters to
attack loyalists of the town's PRI Mayor Jesus Tolentino during the
inauguration ceremony Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Buendia's son had lost the party's mayoral nomination to
Tolentino.
</P>
<P>
   ''The PRI never again wants to see this type of cowardly
incidents of violence for any reason or political motive of any
group,'' Sauri said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 members of Buendia's neighborhood organization
have been jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Local media has described Buendia as a PRI political boss who
spun out of control and ran the town with an iron fist.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ''She Wolf'' as a teen-ager for fighting off two girls
bothering her sister, Buendia already had embarrassed Mexico's
ruling party once for having male strippers perform on Mother's Day
to draw local support for its presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of a bus route and bicycle taxi service, she
subdivided and sold land invaded by squatters and ran a
neighborhood organization. Her husband served as city treasurer;
her cousin and her nephew have been mayor; other family members
served on the city council and in state and federal legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Buendia served five years in prison for extortion. She was freed
in 1999, months before the state elections, Reforma said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
