<HEADLINE> Slaughterhouse escapee finds haven upstate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. (AP) - She narrowly escaped death in a New
York City slaughterhouse then roamed the streets of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   But now Queenie, an 8-month-old, 500-pound calf faces a far
brighter future on the grounds of an upstate New York animal
sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Queenie's odyssey began Wednesday when she escaped from Astoria
Live Poultry to be recaptured some time later.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, workers at the Farm Sanctuary, a 175-acre plot of
land in Schuyler County about 80 miles southwest of Syracuse,
picked up Queenie at the animal holding area at JFK International
Airport and took her home.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter is home to a little more than 500 farm animals,
including goats, sheep, turkeys, rabbits, cattle, ducks, geese and
pigs.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter doesn't buy animals so Aladdin El-Sayed, the owner
of Astoria Live Poultry, donated the calf to the city, telling
Newsday: ''God was willing to give it a new life, so why wouldn't
I?''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his generosity, he faces $3,000 in fines because of the
escape, Newsday reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
