<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos' Davis Rested After Injury  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   When Terrell Davis reported tightness in his left
hamstring,
Denver coach Mike Shanahan was quick to take the star running back
out of Saturday night's exhibition game with Dallas.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''He said he wanted to stay in,'' Shanahan said of Davis, who
blew out his right knee in the fourth game last season. ''I thought
he looked good running the ball, but we didn't want to take any
chances with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, continuing his steady progress from reconstructive knee
surgery, ran for 31 yards on six carries, including a 5-yard
scoring run and an 11-yard gain on his final carry, in the Broncos'
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Of his injury, Davis said, ''It's nothing major. I couldn't
afford to go back out there and actually pull it.''
Rams:
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Martz said offensive tackle Orlando Pace, who
strained his right patella tendon in the first half of Saturday's
game against Buffalo, wasn't seriously hurt. However, Pace will be
held out of the Rams' preseason finale Thursday against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Devin Bush's strained groin also is not serious and he
could practice Monday. Cornerback Dre' Bly has a pulled hamstring
and is questionable for the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams reduced their roster to 69 players, waiving quarterback
Corte McGuffey, defensive end Barry Mitchell, tight end Alex Hass,
linebacker Bert Berry, running back D'Andre Hardeman and cornerback
Darwin Brown.
Giants:
</P>
<P>
   Fred Lewis, the free-agent cornerback who fumbled away a
preseason victory after being tackled in the end zone by a teammate
against Jacksonville, was among 12 players cut by New York.
</P>
<P>
   Also waived were halfback Omar Bacon, quarterback Bill Burke,
defensive ends Lavell Ellis and Cedric Pittman, defensive lineman
Carl Hansen, defensive tackle Faiva Talaeai, guard John Kuzora,
tight end Mark Thomas, wide receivers Anthony Tucker and Jeremy
Watkins and safety B.J. Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie linebacker Dhani Jones was placed on the injured reserve
list with a knee injury, and free-agent linebacker Vernon
Strickland, who tore injured a knee in the on Aug. 11 game against
Jacksonville, was waived-injured.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Brody Heffner-Liddiard, a free agent from Colorado who
was cut by Minnesota last week, was signed Sunday because of his
long-snapping ability.
Panthers:
</P>
<P>
   Veteran linebacker Donta Jones was among seven players waived by
Carolina. Also cut were offensive linemen Rob Bohlinger and Allen
Mogridge, wide receiver Michael Dean, running back Derek O'Neal,
linebacker Jason Parmer and defensive back Kevin Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   Coach George Seifert also said kicker Brian Gowins and wide
receiver Octavus Barnes were let go, but the waivers wouldn't be
made official with the league until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Jim Turner, defensive back Tony Booth, defensive
lineman Robert Daniel and safety Deon Grant -- all four out for the
season -- were placed on injured reserve.
Seahawks:
</P>
<P>
   Seattle released eight players, including six-year veteran wide
receiver Justin Armour and rookie quarterback Kevin Feterik.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, general manager-coach Mike Holmgren released wide
receivers Ben Clampitt and Ricky Garrett, offensive tackle Tim
Conley, guard Donta Kendrick, linebacker Carlos Timmons and
cornerback Omar Evans, all rookies.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks placed cornerback Fred Vinson (knee) and center
Robbie Tobeck (knee) on the physically unable to perform list, and
tight end Rufus French (knee) on injured reserve.
Jets:
</P>
<P>
   Otis Smith was one of eight players cut by New York as the Jets
got the roster down to 62. Smith had a poor game Friday night
against the New York Giants and generally struggled throughout the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Other veterans waived were linebacker Casey Dailey,
predominantly a special teams player; tackle Ian Rafferty; and wide
receiver Fred Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Four rookies were cut: defensive tackle Richard Seals,
linebackers Brent Naccara and Kelvin Moses and fullback Mike
Stack.
Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona cut nine rookie free agents from their roster, leaving
the team with 71 players. The Cardinals must make six more roster
moves to reach the 65-player limit Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Those cut were running back Keith Brown, cornerback Renard Cox,
punter Greg Debolt, defensive end Terrell Jurineack, quarterback
Sean Keenan, fullback Matt Keller, wide receiver John Shoemaker,
tackle Robert Skapura and guard David Walden.
Vikings:
</P>
<P>
   Left guard Corbin Lacina will be sidelined for at least two
weeks and possibly a month because of a sprained knee.
</P>
<P>
   Lacina sprained the medial collateral ligament in his right knee
on the Vikings' first offensive play in Friday night's victory over
Arizona. He returned for the second series but then left to undergo
an MRI exam.
</P>
<P>
   The test revealed no tear, but his availability for the Vikings'
regular-season opener against Chicago is in doubt.
</P>
</TEXT>
