<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Burkina Faso Bodyguards Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) -- Two bodyguards of Burkina
Faso's president have been sentenced to 20 years in prison for
torturing to death the driver of the president's brother.
</P>
<P>
   A third bodyguard was sentenced to 10 years without parole, and
two more were acquitted. A military tribunal handed down the
verdicts Saturday night in this semi-desert West African nation.
</P>
<P>
   The men were tried in the death of David Ouedraogo, the
chauffeur for President Blaise Compaore's younger brother,
Francois.
</P>
<P>
   Ouedraogo was suspected of having stolen $31,000 belonging to
Francois Compaore. The bodyguards were accused of torturing him to
death in an attempt to find out where the money was hidden.
Ouedraogo died of his injuries in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, two of Ouedraogo's friends, who were also
tortured, said the guards sometimes ''parachuted'' their victims --
dragging them naked down a rocky hill. The guards also tied them
upside down from trees and then burned them with torches to get
them to talk, the two said.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, one of the guards described the tortures as
''military maneuvers'' to get to the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The trial has been closely watched in Burkina Faso. Ouedraogo's
death sparked a newspaper investigation by local journalist Robert
Zongo -- who was subsequently burned to death in his car along with
two of his cousins and his driver in December.
</P>
<P>
   Zongo's death touched off violent strikes and street
demonstrations against Compaore's government. The five bodyguards
were named as ''serious suspects'' by an investigative commission,
but the investigation has stalled and no progress has been
announced in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this sentence will help ease the tension in the
country,'' public prosecutor Abdoulaye Barry said after the
Saturday night announcement of the verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   Compaore, who has won two presidential elections since taking
power following a violent coup in 1987, had been accused of using
his influence to prevent the judiciary from prosecuting the cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''This trial has allowed us to know the quality of the persons
who govern us,'' said Ouedraogo's brother, Arthur, after the
verdict was announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-20-00 2143 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
