<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Golfs, Hillary Campaigns  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. (AP) -- President Clinton closed a short family
vacation with a brisk round of golf Sunday, while his wife, a
Senate candidate, cleared out early to campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton family holed up in upstate New York's Adirondack
Mountains to celebrate Clinton's 54th birthday and to stay mostly
out of sight as Vice President Gore began his post-convention
campaign swing.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, running for the Senate seat being
vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, bookended the holiday with
political appearances. Friday night she and the president both
spoke to a local Democrat Party picnic, and on Sunday she left
their woodsy retreat for campaign appearances in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   When she left, the president was playing 18 holes on a
picturesque golf course skirted by the mountains. Afterwards,
during a stop back at his weekend residence, Clinton caught a
little of the PGA Championship on television, including a dramatic
moment when it was tied after 72 holes. Then he left in his
motorcade to drop by a friend's home.
</P>
<P>
   During a stop to shake hands, a man asked the president why he'd
quit watching the golf tournament before its conclusion with Tiger
Woods' history-making victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''A golfer like you and you're leaving before it's over?'' the
man shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a crew-rest issue on my airplane,'' Clinton told him.
''Unfortunately, I don't have a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   He ended his visit to Lake Placid late Sunday and flew to the
Clintons' New York home in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a bizarre bit of street theater in which a woman
asked Clinton to sign her T-shirt, then peeled the T-shirt over her
head, the family's short getaway was uneventful.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton set the tone for the weekend when he told local
Democrats that he is now neither his family's candidate nor his
party's leader.
</P>
<P>
   From now on, Clinton said, he is going to be a ''citizen
activist.''
</P>
<P>
   That lower profile did not stop Clinton from shaking hands along
the route of his motorcade, and the family drew an enthusiastic
crowd when they stopped for ice cream after a birthday dinner in
town Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The woman with the T-shirt was among well-wishers along Main
Street in Lake Placid. Her apparently impromptu stunt was more
shocking for its audacity than for the degree of skin exposed. She
had mostly turned her back on Clinton by the time she removed her
shirt and exposed her brassiere.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday, the family hiked the rugged pine woods of the
estate of Arthur Lussi, a local real estate developer who, although
a Republican, offered his home to the family for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Lussi and his father, Serge Lussi, were in the President's
eight-player party Sunday at the Lake Placid Resort. The Lussi
family owns that as well.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the group was a longtime New York Democratic backer,
Barry Wigmore, whose golf technique was less than polished. Wigmore
showed up early to practice, but still needed two shots to get his
ball only about 60 yards down the first fairway.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Clinton drove a long, straight shot toward the
hole, then stepped back from the tee with evident satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Word filtered through the club house later that Wigmore was
riding in a golf cart with the party but was no longer playing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-20-00 2145 </TRAILER>
