<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians: No Deal With Israel  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE COPANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The Palestinian cabinet insisted there will be
no compromise with Israel on the key issue of Jerusalem, in a tough
statement Sunday coinciding with U.S. envoy Dennis Ross' efforts to
revive Mideast peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the debate became more acrimonious as Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak said it was now up to the Palestinians to make
the next move in peace efforts, while a Palestinian official warned
that Jewish settlers in the West Bank and Gaza could become
hostages if a crisis erupted.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian cabinet said Israel must withdraw from east
Jerusalem, which would become the Palestinian capital. ''The
Jerusalem issue is not negotiable and cannot be so today, tomorrow
or in the future,'' the cabinet said in a communique distributed by
WAFA, the Palestinian news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Ahmed Abdel Rahman, the Palestinian Authority's
secretary-general warned that if Israel were to annex parts of the
West Bank in retaliation for a unilateral Palestinian declaration
of independence, the Jewish settlers would become hostages.
</P>
<P>
   ''Israel has a presence in the Palestinian lands which would be
on the level of hostages in the hands of Palestinians,'' he told
the Voice of Palestine radio. ''These ... settlements that are in
the Palestinian lands will become isolated and will face a real
danger if Israel closed off all territories from all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak has hinted that if Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
declares a state unilaterally, he might annex areas of the West
Bank or seal off the Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Barak told his Cabinet that the ball was in the
Palestinians' court. ''We are in a waiting period since we have yet
to hear from them about an openness and willingness to discuss the
ideas that were raised at Camp David,'' Barak said, according to a
Cabinet statement.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. envoy Ross was in the region in an effort to prod the sides
along, following the collapse of the Camp David summit last month
over competing claims to Jerusalem. Sunday evening he met
Palestinian negotiators Saeb Erekat and Mohammed Dahlan at an
undisclosed location in Jerusalem, said a Palestinian official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have set a Sept. 13 deadline for a final peace
accord. Arafat has said in the past that he has the right to
declare an independent state unilaterally, if no accord is reached
by then. However, he and other Palestinian leaders have strongly
indicated that date will be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, amid a flurry of diplomatic activity in the region
following Camp David's collapse, Syria's Foreign Minister Farouk
al-Sharaa visited Saudi Arabia and Egypt to discuss the status of
Jerusalem. Syrian President Bashar Assad is to visit the two
countries this week in his first trip abroad since he took over as
president after his father's death in June.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Sunday, a Palestinian boy was killed in the southern
West Bank when he stepped on unexploded ammunition -- apparently a
grenade -- close to a former Israeli army firing range.
</P>
<P>
   Moeen Talakhme, 13, was walking from his home in the village of
Kafr al-Burj to pick figs when he stepped on the explosive, his
father Mohammed Talakhme said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1987, 34 Palestinians have been killed and more than 90
injured by unexploded Israeli ammunition in the West Bank, said
Tomer Feffer, spokesman the Israeli human rights group Betselem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
