<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> May Shows How He Kept the Faith  </HEADLINE>
By JIM LITKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- He was playing for the Roy McAvoys of the
world, for all those ''Tin Cup'' golf pros, real or imagined, with
more longing than sense.
</P>
<P>
   And so the first question to Bob May after one of the more
spectacular afternoons golf has ever seen should not have been,
''How did you almost beat Tiger Woods?'' but ''What kept you
believing you'd ever get the chance?''
</P>
<P>
   This is the story of the promising junior golfer who runs out of
results long before he runs out of desire. About the golfer who
knows a date with destiny awaits him somewhere down the road, only
he can't convince anybody to give him the car keys.
</P>
<P>
   In one of those turns that sports love to take, May, who at 31
is seven years older, was Woods before Woods came along. He burned
up the same Southern California junior circuit. He set down the
standard of excellence that Woods trampled before Woods set his
sights on Jack Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not trying to toot my own horn, but in some newspaper
articles, when he was a little, Tiger would say, 'I'm going to beat
all of Bob May's records.'
</P>
<P>
   ''He kept saying it and doing it, saying and doing it, saying
and doing it. And today,'' May said, pausing, ''I thought maybe
this was my chance to get him back.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time he said that to himself, May had no idea how long
it would take to get that chance. He was a college star at Oklahoma
State, played on the 1991 Walker Cup team alongside Phil Mickelson
and turned pro soon afterward, bankrolled by actor Joe Pesci, DJ
Rick Dees and a few other high-rollers from Bel-Aire Country Club
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Barely three years later, his return on the investment had
dwindled to a joke. He earned $31,079 for the season, enough to
rank him No. 209 and too little to keep his PGA playing card. Even
tougher, May knew deep down, he'd lost his game.
</P>
<P>
   That's when May swallowed his pride and went into exile, willing
to scrap for his second chance. He spent more time in Europe over
the next five years than Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. On
that tour, playing in harsher weather, over scruffier courses,
against golfers just as hungry, May regained the toughness that
made so feared as a kid. With it, came some badly needed momentum.
</P>
<P>
   First, May beat European stars Colin Montgomerie and Lee
Westwood at the British Masters. That gave him an exemption into
this PGA Championship. Next up was a 13th-place finish at the PGA
Tour qualifying school to regain his full-time playing privileges.
He played in 17 tournaments, made the cut in 13 and finished second
in June at the FedEx St. Jude Classic. Few people still knew him,
but May knew his game had returned.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think you could come over here and not be ready to
play,'' he said, ''because you've got Tiger Woods, David Duval,
Ernie Els, you've got the best players in the world over here.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just May's luck to draw the best of the best in the
season's last major. It seemed like such an epic mismatch at first
that more than a few people no doubt turned on the TV set Sunday
and wondered whether they had stumbled into a remake of ''Tin
Cup.'' But nobody who saw May play a few shots was tempted to
change the channel.
</P>
<P>
   May punched and Woods counterpunched. They traded iron shots at
the flag, buried putts on top of one another and time and again,
salvaged par from near-certain disaster. Soon enough, the roars
that broke out from every corner of the course subsided and began
gathering on every hole where May and Woods took their fight. It
was like somebody turned up the volume and then yanked off the
knob.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was tough out there,'' May said. ''At one point I turned to
Tiger and said, 'Is this what you get every week?' And he said,
'You got it.'
</P>
<P>
   May believed as a kid he would arrive at this place some day,
just not by such a circuitous route.
</P>
<P>
   His rise through the game -- the first time, anyway -- came with
breathtaking speed. May didn't come from a golfing family; his
father owned a filling station and never played the game. He
cobbled together a set from the single clubs his aunt gave him each
year from Christmas. But the first time he stepped on a practice
tee at age 8&AMP;frac12;, May was a natural. Shot after shot disappeared into
the distance.
</P>
<P>
   The search for that swing, for that sense of control once more,
took May more than 20 years, on a detour to Europe and back. It
seems amazing that he found it in the rollicking hillside outside
Louisville, playing alongside the very kid he knew all those years
ago would be tough to shake.
</P>
<P>
   More amazing still, though, is that he never gave up.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
