<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polls: Salazar Leads Fox in Chiapas  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUXTLA GUTIERREZ, Mexico (AP) -- Supporters of a candidate allied
to Mexico's president-elect celebrated in the streets after they
said a series of exit polls showed their favorite ahead in Sunday's
gubernatorial election.
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Salazar is seeking to end the long domination of Mexico's
impoverished Chiapas state by the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, pledging to step up efforts to end the six-year-old
Zapatista rebellion there.
</P>
<P>
   The election is seen as a major test of the PRI's ability to
rebound after Vicente Fox won Mexico's presidency on July 2 and
ended the PRI's 71-year reign in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Television station TV Azteca reported its poll showed Salazar --
a member of the eight-party coalition led by Fox -- with a 53-46
percent lead over the PRI's Sami David.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the National Actional Party or PAN, a coalition
member, said that exit polls by four independent organizations show
Salazar ahead by 7 to 17 percentage points. ''All of the polls
agree in saying that the indisputable winner'' is Salazar, PAN
leader Luis Felipe Bravo Mena told journalists in Tuxtla Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
   But PRI officials immediately questioned the polls' validity and
said their surveys showed David ahead in the vote for governor of
Chiapas. ''We have different information,'' David told state
television.
</P>
<P>
   First official results were not expected until after 11 p.m.,
but the TV Azteca report sent Salazar supporters into the streets
of Tuxtla Gutierrez, honking car horns, waving flags and screaming
in joy.
</P>
<P>
   Little more than a decade ago, Chiapas' was the PRI's
stronghold, producing votes of more than 90 percent for the party.
</P>
<P>
   But the still-unresolved Zapatista revolt looms over Chiapas
politics. The past six years have seen four governors, three of
them emergency replacements for men driven from office by crises
linked to the Zapatista revolt.
</P>
<P>
   President-elect Fox had said a Salazar victory would help him
reach agreement with the Zapatistas by showing that the path to
change was through the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar, who had been shown leading in pre-election polls, has
vowed to focus on negotiations with the rebels while cracking down
on paramilitary groups he says have been encouraged by the current
state and federal governments.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatista National Revolutionary Army rebelled on Jan. 1,
1994, demanding justice and democracy for Chiapas' Indians. Though
open warfare lasted only two weeks, the guerrilla presence in the
state's jungle canyons has led to repeated clashes between
emboldened dissident groups and pro-government forces.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's voting, electoral officials and observers had
reported only scattered problems.
</P>
<P>
   For some, however, voting was an act of courage.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors of a 1997 massacre of 45 people in the village of
Acteal marched for four hours through the mountains to vote in Los
Chorros, the town that had expelled them and home to many of their
paramilitary attackers. There were no polling places for absentee
voters in the towns where the refugees are sheltered.
</P>
<P>
   ''The greatest fear the people have in coming to the polls is
suffering an attack by the paramilitaries along the way,'' said
Agustin Vasquez Ruiz, spokesman for the Las Abejas group of
refugees from the Los Chorros area.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,000 polling places were scattered throughout Mexico's
poorest and most rural state, one where disputes over land,
religion and Indian rights have often erupted into violence. It is
a tough place to govern.
</P>
<P>
   In 176 years, the state has had more than 160 governors --
despite Mexico's practice of six-year terms over the past six
decades.
</P>
<P>
   On the day before the vote in the Zapatista village of San Jose
del Rio in the Lacandon jungle, residents expressed wariness of any
politician.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose del Rio is only 105 miles from this state capital, but
a hard six-hour's drive, some on tracks unpassable to most cars.
</P>
<P>
   The region's impoverished coffee farmers describe themselves as
rebel ''sympathizers,'' but they show the discipline of Zapatista
stalwarts. While friendly, few will talk politics. None will give
his name, saying they are forbidden to do so. All say they are
''neutral'' in the election, echoing Zapatista communiques.
</P>
<P>
   Salazar is a former PRI senator who quit the party last year. As
senator, he was a member of a commission that negotiated a partial
peace deal with the Zapatistas rejected by the federal government.
He says his election would be a key element in bringing peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not friends'' with the Zapatistas, he said in a recent
interview. ''I know them from the negotiations. I am not a
Zapatista. But they have a great advantage with me: I am not
anti-Zapatista.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wants to give the Zapatistas ''the dignified out they
have been fighting for a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
