<HEADLINE> Polls: Mexico Pro-Fox Has Lead  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUXTLA GUTIERREZ, Mexico (AP) -- Supporters of a candidate allied
to Mexico's president-elect celebrated in the streets after they
said a series of exit polls showed their favorite ahead in Sunday's
gubernatorial election.
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Salazar is seeking to end the long domination of Mexico's
impoverished Chiapas state by the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, pledging to step up efforts to end the six-year-old
Zapatista rebellion there.
</P>
<P>
   The election is seen as a major test of the PRI's ability to
rebound after Vicente Fox won Mexico's presidency on July 2 and
ended the PRI's 71-year reign in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Television station TV Azteca reported its poll showed Salazar --
a member of the eight-party coalition led by Fox -- with a 53-46
percent lead over the PRI's Sami David.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the National Actional Party or PAN, a coalition
member, said that exit polls by four independent organizations show
Salazar ahead by 7 to 17 percentage points. ''All of the polls
agree in saying that the indisputable winner'' is Salazar, PAN
leader Luis Felipe Bravo Mena told journalists in Tuxtla Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
   But PRI officials immediately questioned the polls' validity and
said their surveys showed David ahead in the vote for governor of
Chiapas. ''We have different information,'' David told state
television.
</P>
<P>
   First official results were not expected until after 11 p.m.,
but the TV Azteca report sent Salazar supporters into the streets
of Tuxtla Gutierrez, honking car horns, waving flags and screaming
in joy.
</P>
<P>
   Little more than a decade ago, Chiapas' was the PRI's
stronghold, producing votes of more than 90 percent for the party.
</P>
<P>
   But the still-unresolved Zapatista revolt looms over Chiapas
politics. The past six years have seen four governors, three of
