<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moroccan King Announces Oil Find  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RABAT, Morocco (AP) -- King Mohammed VI said Sunday that a large
field of oil and gas had been discovered near Morocco's eastern
border.
</P>
<P>
   The king said the find ''was good-quality and abundant,'' but he
did not specify the amount discovered near Talsint, about 60 miles
from the border with gas-rich Algeria, the official MAP news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco has had no important oil or natural gas reserves,
importing virtually all its fuel.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, some independent Moroccan media speculated that the
underground store could contain up to 20 billion barrels of oil.
But Moroccan Energy Minister Youssef Tahiri in July called the
reports ''fantastic and premature,'' saying only that there were
encouraging signs of oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a festival for young people, the king said the
natural resources should be ''used rationally, to ensure the
relaunching of the national economy and social development.''
</P>
<P>
   Since taking the throne after the death last summer of his
father, Hassan II, the 37-year-old ruler has made efforts to
modernize the North African kingdom with measures to promote
literacy and fight poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based Lone Star Technologies Inc. has been searching for
oil on land and in the waters off Morocco's long Atlantic Coast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
