<DOCNO> APW20000820.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Begay, Cink Make Presidents Cup  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS DUNCAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Notah Begay and Stewart Cink won the
tournament within the tournament -- qualifying for the Presidents
Cup -- in the PGA Championship on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Begay and Cink moved into the top 10 in the points standings,
based on PGA Tour earnings from the start of the 1999 season, to
gain automatic berths on the 12-member U.S. team. Captain Ken
Venturi will make two wild-card picks Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The matches against the International team will be played Oct.
19-22 at the Robert Trent Jones Golf Club in Gainsville, Va. The
International team is made up of foreign, non-European players.
</P>
<P>
   Begay shot a 70 on Sunday to finish eighth in the PGA. He earned
$145,000 to vault from 11th to eighth in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no Olympics for golfers, so it's the closest thing.
I'll be proud to wear the red, white and blue,'' Begay said.
</P>
<P>
   Cink, who entered the tournament 10th in the standings, tied for
14th in the PGA to hold the No. 10 position.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a major and that was more important than the
Presidents Cup team. I didn't want to just play this as a
Presidents Cup qualifier, but it's hard not to,'' Cink said. ''This
is a goal I've had all year and this is the final event for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods topped the points race with 20,002,228, followed by
Phil Mickelson, Hal Sutton, David Duval, Davis Love III, Tom
Lehman, Jim Furyk.
</P>
<P>
   Loren Roberts, who dropped from ninth to 11th, wasn't optimistic
about being selected as a captain's pick.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really wanted to make the team this year,'' Roberts said.
''I've been playing really consistent all year. But it's been a
long summer and unfortunately, I ran out of gas one week too
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Perry remained 12th in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was an ice hockey player growing up and was captain of my
team. I'm a fighter and a grinder,'' said Perry, who was 27th on
the PGA Tour money list entering the week. ''I scratch and claw for
as much as I can get out of a round.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry said a berth would be especially satisfying because Ben
Crenshaw left him off the Ryder Cup team in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've made it known since then that my next goal was to win
tournaments or to make the Presidents Cup,'' Perry said.
''(Venturi) has got a tough job and I don't know if he's going to
go off the board and pick somebody. I just would really would like
to be part of a team atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Triplett, who finished ninth in the points standings after
a final-round 72, said Venturi would be smart to select players who
have never been on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ''It'll be good for the other guys on the team to have guys who
are enthusiastic about playing,'' Triplett said. ''We'd all be
relative rookies whereas everybody above us has played in a number
of these things. They look at it more as a duty, probably, than
something they're really excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry said that's what would make him a good choice.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if a lot of other players have stressed that
point, but I really want to play on the team,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been in the hunt a lot and yeah, I haven't come through a
lot. But get me in an atmosphere like that and I'm going to be like
a Payne Stewart or Hal Sutton. If they just want me sitting on the
sidelines, that's fine. I'll be out there cheering with my pom-pons
ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The International team is based on the world rankings, with
South Africa's Retief Goosen locking up the 10th spot after missing
the cut in the PGA. Australia's Robert Allenby finished 11th
despite tying for fourth in the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's Ernie Els, No. 2 in the world behind Woods,
topped the team, followed by Fiji's Vijay Singh, Zimbabwe's Nick
Price, Paraguay's Carlos Franco, Australia's Stuart Appleby, New
Zealand's Michael Campbell, Canada's Mike Weir, Japan's Shigeki
Maruyama, and Australia's Greg Norman. Weir is the first Canadian
to make the team.
</P>
<P>
   International team captain Peter Thomson also will announce two
wild-card picks Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
