<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hill Chosen To Head U.S. Gymnastics  </HEADLINE>
By EDDIE PELLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Officials at USA Gymnastics surprised some experts
by choosing outspoken Kelli Hill as head coach of the U.S. Olympic
team Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, the personal coach of Olympians Dominique Dawes and Elise
Ray, was as shocked as anyone after being chosen over favorite Mary
Lee Tracy, who coaches Olympian Morgan White and alternate Alyssa
Beckerman.
</P>
<P>
   Hill has been an outspoken opponent of the Olympic selection
procedure, a stance she was sure doomed her chances to be head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't expect this at all, to be honest,'' she said. ''It's
because of my outspokenness on all kinds of issues, and how I felt
about the procedure. I thought I gave this dream up when I spoke
out. It's definitely a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy will serve as assistant coach, the same position she held
in 1996. She handled the decision with class and said she was happy
to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, it was Dawes who benefited most from the selection
procedure her coach disliked.
</P>
<P>
   Dawes finished seventh in the weighted scoring from nationals
and trials. She wouldn't have made it had it not been for the
system, in which a committee led by Bela Karolyi chose six athletes
without being beholden to the scores.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hill's ability to get Dawes ready for her third Olympics
in the three months since she announced her comeback that may have
spoken loudest about her coaching credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very ironic,'' Hill said. ''But I just have to pray it
was the best thing for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   USA Gymnastics president Bob Colarossi said Hill's outspokenness
didn't bother him or Karolyi.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has two athletes on the team, she has proven international
experience and a lot of Olympic medals in her pocket, so I think
she'll do a great job for us,'' Colarossi said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill also coached the U.S. team at the 1999 world championships.
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi is the national team coordinator and will be at the
Olympics, but he's not the coach. One of the biggest questions
surrounding the U.S. team is how much contact he'll have with the
gymnasts during competition in Sydney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-20-00 2256 </TRAILER>
