<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-20 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Sunday, Aug. 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Verizon, Unions Make 'Tentative' Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Verizon Communications and unions representing 50,000
workers reached a tentative agreement tonight on a new three-year-contract as a
two-week strike affecting 25 million phone users in the East neared an end. The
agreement was struck with the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers
and one of two bargaining units for the Communications Workers of America
covering employees in New York and New England. Negotiations with another
bargaining unit for the CWA -- covering more than 35,000 workers in the Middle
Atlantic states -- continued this evening.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Polls: Salazar Leads in Chiapas
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TUXTLA GUTIERREZ, Mexico (AP) -- Supporters of a candidate allied to Mexico's
president-elect Vicente Fox celebrated in the streets after they said a series
of exit polls showed their favorite ahead in Sunday's gubernatorial election.
Pablo Salazar is seeking to end the long domination of Mexico's impoverished
Chiapas state by the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, pledging to step
up efforts to end the six-year-old Zapatista rebellion there. The election is
seen as a major test of the PRI's ability to rebound after Fox won Mexico's
presidency on July 2 and ended the PRI's 71-year reign in Mexico.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mexico's PRI Admits To Violent History
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's ruling party admits it has tolerated violent
political bosses among its ranks -- but swears not to do so anymore after a
post-election battle that left at least 10 dead, local media said Sunday. Armed
supporters of a longtime political boss aligned with the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, opened fire on thousands of loyalists of
Chimalhuacan's new mayor Friday in the gritty city of 490,000 on the outskirts
of Mexico City. ''The PRI takes its historic responsibility for having tolerated
leaders and groups in the party whose condemnable conduct causes harm and
destroys,'' the PRI's national leader Dulce Maria Sauri told the Mexico City
newspaper Reforma. ''But today we say enough is enough! Never again!''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rescuers Cannot Get In Russian Sub
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- After struggling unsuccessfully to open the escape hatch on a
nuclear submarine that sank with 118 men aboard, Norwegian divers could find no
sign of life Sunday. Russian officials said most of the vessel was flooded in
minutes when it went down and the country's navy has all but ruled out hope that
any of the crew remains alive nine days after the Kursk sank, crippled by a
massive explosion. The divers, working 350 feet below the surface of the Barents
Sea, found signs that some of the 118 crewmen may have tried to get out but were
unable to open the escape hatch.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N.M. Pipeline Explosion Kills 10
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, N.M. (AP) -- An explosion of a natural gas pipeline just before
dawn today swept flames down the river's banks and through the tents where two
families had been camping, killing 10 people, five of them children. The only
survivors, a man and his daughter-in-law, were in critical condition today at a
Lubbock, Texas, hospital. Officials described the ruptured pipeline as a massive
flame-thrower that showered burning fuel on the victims. The explosion generated
heat so intense that sand melted into glass and concrete turned to powder, a
federal investigator said Sunday. Investigators say it likely will take several
months to determine what caused the rupture in the 30-inch-diameter pipe.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Power Outages Continue in N.C.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- About 1,800 North Carolina homes and businesses were
still without power tonight as crews worked to restore service knocked out
Friday by severe storms. Two deaths were blamed on the storms that pounded the
state with heavy rain, wind, lightning and hail. Duke Energy said more than
17,000 outages remained this morning but the company was down to 1,800 by late
evening, mostly in the Charlotte area.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japanese Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices fell in early trading Monday following a
slip on Wall Street Friday. The Nikkei fell 64.77 points, or 0.39 percent, in
the first 30 minutes of morning trading. The index had gained 119.46 points, or
0.74 percent, Friday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Woods Wins PGA Title in Playoff
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Tiger Woods today birdied the last two holes in
regulation and won the PGA Championship in a playoff over Bob May, becoming the
first player since Ben Hogan in 1953 to win three majors in one year. Both made
five birdies, two sensational par saves and had a 31 on the back nine. Woods
outlasted May by taking only three putts in the three-hole playoff, the last one
a 2-foot par putt for his third consecutive major.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by GRETCHEN SCHWARTZ
