<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police call off search for man presumed drowned  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SCHAGHTICOKE, N.Y. (AP) - Police suspended the search for a
19-year-old Schaghticoke man who fell into the Hoosick River Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Larry Chuba was walking along a log when he slipped
and fell five feet into the river's fast moving waters.
</P>
<P>
   Chuba's friend jumped in to save him but could not reach him.
Several attempts to reach Chuba with wood branches failed and his
friend ran a half-mile to a nearby gas station and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen divers searched the river for four hours and a
helicopter used heat seeking devices to search for Chuba's body.
The search was called off when darkness fell.
</P>
<P>
   One of Chuba's boots was found and officials believe he removed
it to make himself lighter.
</P>
<P>
   The search will continue beginning at eight Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Schaghticoke is about 20 miles northeast of Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
